<HEAD>
    <TITLE>BIOS OF 1995 FELLOWS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H2><CENTER>BIOGRAPHIES OF 1995 GW FELLOWS<BR>
<HR></CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
<B>MARK DeFORREST</B> attends Gonzaga University School of Law in Spokane,
where he is a recipient of a Thomas More Scholarship. A graduate in History
from Western Washington University, he has also studied at the Franciscan
School of Theology in Berkeley. He has wide experience working among AIDS
patients and the homeless. His writing project focused on the use of religious
language in politics.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SPENCER DENNISON</B> attends Marietta College in Ohio, where he is studying
Political Science and History and maintains a 4.0 GPA. He is a weekly political
columnist for the campus newspaper, plays rugby, and is active in campus
and community affairs. During the summer, he has worked as a legislative
intern for Ohio Representative Joseph Haines. His writing project examined
the effect of government programs on moral character.<BR>
<BR>
A<B>LEXANDRA GRAY</B> is a recent graduate in Mathematics and International
Studies of Oglethorpe University in Atlanta, where she received the James
Edward Oglethorpe Award for scholarship and service. She is presently pursuing
post-graduate work at Mercer University. She has been a Rotary Exchange
Student in Denmark and taught English at Seigakuin General Research Institute,
Seigakuin University, Japan. Her writing project explored the relationship
between religion and education.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SCOTT JONES</B> attends John Brown University in Arkansas, where he is
studying History and Theology. A recipient of a Presidential Scholarship,
he has been Chaplain of the campus Honors Society and is active in student
government. He has also served as an instructor in the University's Center
for Academic Achievement, and during the summer of 1994, he worked in Tiberias,
Israel. His writing project addressed the religious case against prayer
in public schools.<BR>
<BR>
<B>JOB NELSON</B> is a graduate student in the doctoral degree program in
Public Policy at The Claremont Graduate School. He is co-author with Steve
Hayward of the Index of Leading Environmental Indicators., and in 1993 he
received a Summer Research Fellowship from the Pacific Research Institute
in San Francisco. His writing project explored the moral and religious dimensions
of biotechnology research.<BR>
<BR>
<B>DAVID NOLLAND</B> is a 1995 honors graduate of Trinity College, Cambridge
University, where he studied Mathematics and Theoretical Physics. He is
presently continuing his studies in Mathematics at Cambridge. He has traveled
extensively around the world and worked among inner city children and single-parent
families. His writing project analyzed the relationship between Christian
thought and the methodology of theoretical science.<BR>
<BR>
<B>CATHERINE NORMAN </B>is a 1995 graduate in History of the University
of Washington. Her studies focused on Eastern Europe and the history of
Christianity. She speaks Mandarin Chinese and has served as an intern for
U. S. Senator Slade Gorton. Her writing project explored the status of religious
liberty in modern Greece.<BR>
<B><BR>
DEREK SARAFA</B> attends the University of Michigan Law School (where he
transferred after a year at Notre Dame University Law School). A member
of several honor societies, he graduated with high honors in 1994 from James
Madison College of Michigan State University, where he studied Political
Economy and Political Theory. He has served as a policy analyst for the
Michigan Nonprofit Forum and as a research assistant at the Institute for
Public Policy and Social Research. His writing project discussed natural
law and civil disobedience.<BR>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="1995gwf.html"><IMG SRC="dymored-back.gif" WIDTH="78"
HEIGHT="17" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></CENTER>
