<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Summar of 1995 Program</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H2><CENTER>SUMMARY OF THE 1995 PROGRAM AND ITS IMPACT<BR>
<HR></CENTER>
</H2>
The George Washington Fellows met nearly every weekday with Dr. West to
discuss readings ranging from the Bible and Martin Luther to the American
Founders and C. S. Lewis. Key themes explored through the readings include
the special role of religion in fostering civic morality, the importance
of religious liberty, the need to find common ground with other citizens
when entering public life, and the necessity of humility and charity in
politics (&quot;speaking the truth in love&quot;) to counter the temptations
of power. A special emphasis of the readings was the positive impact of
faith on American public life during the past two centuries, including the
efforts by nineteenth century evangelicals to defend the human rights of
the Cherokee Indians and African Americans. This year the seminar added
a special set of readings from Karl Marx, Charles Darwin, and others, showing
the debilitating effects of materialism on Western culture. As in the 1994
program, postbaccalaureate, graduate-level credit was available for the
seminar through Seattle Pacific University, and two students took the course
for credit.<BR>
