<P>
<li> There is yet another complicating
factor to consider.  NOx emissions from mobile and stationary
sources become nitrogen pollution in rivers, lakes and streams,
which leads to eutrophication and fish kills. This in turn leads
to a water shed management problem, which is again local or regional
in character.  (On this, see Todd Shields, &quot;Scientist Tracks
Bad Pollution Back to Stacks in the Midwest,&quot; <U>The Washington
Post</U>, April 30, 1996, p. B1, B5.) 
<P>
<li> The seminal work on this problem
is by Nobel Laureate Ronald H. Coase.  (See Ronald H. Coase, &quot;The
Problem of Social Cost,&quot; <U>Journal of Law &amp; Economics</U>,
Vol. 3, October, 1960, pp. 1-44.  Also, see Hugh H. Macaulay and
Bruce Yandle, <U>Environmental Use and the Market</U>, Lexington,
MA:  D. C. Heath and Company, 1977.)
<P>
<li> The seminal argument here was made
by A. C. Pigou. (A.C. Pigou, <U>The Economics of Welfare</U>,
London:  Macmillan and Company, 1920.)
<P>
<li> On this as well as a useful summary
of the relative effectiveness of different policy instruments,
see Arnold W. Reitze, Jr., &quot;A Century of Air Pollution Control
Law:  What's Worked; What's Failed; What Might Work,&quot; <U>Environmental
Law</U>, Vol. 21, 1991, pp. 1549-1647.  Reitze notes that common
law protection that might still be effective for controlling pollution
from easily identified sources has been eroded by statutes that
blunted the evolution of federal common law applied by federal
courts.  For a more optimistic view, see Elizabeth Brubaker, <U>Property
Rights in the Defence of Nature</U>, Toronto: Earthscan Publications
Limited, 1995.
