<head>
<title>Cyberspace and the American Dream -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>



<h1><center>Cyberspace and the American Dream</center></h1>
<p>

The driving force behind the Big Change now happening in America is the
information revolution. PFF has led the way through its Cyberspace and the
American Dream project in exploring the consequences and the direct policy
implications of this revolution.<p>

The Foundation not only dedicated two major conferences to this topic, but it has
published "<A HREF="/pff/position.html">A Magna Carta for the Knowledge Age</A>." This Magna Carta became the
centerpiece of a wide-ranging debate in The Internet and throughout the media
about whether the information revolution was better defined by the metaphor of
"an information superhighway" or the much freer metaphor of "Cyberspace."<p>

But the Foundation's efforts in Cyberspace are by no means limited to vision.
Policy change is taking place in Washington, in state legislatures, indeed, in
governments around the world, as policymakers attempt to understand the
consequences of the move from an analog to a digital world and its impact on
regulatory policy. PFF is actively involved in the telecommunications policy
debate in Washington and around the country, focusing its efforts on the next
generation of telecommunications deregulation. <p>

For example, the Foundation will be offering in May 1995 a complete plan to
abolish the <A HREF="http://www.fcc.gov/">Federal Communications Commission</A>. In addition, PFF is offering in
conjunction with <A HREF="http://www.gmu.edu/">George Mason University</A> an eight-week seminar on
Telecommunications for Capitol Hill staffers. The goal is to educate
"non-experts" about the Information Revolution and the impact action in <A HREF="http://thomas.loc.gov/home/thomas.html">Congress</A>
will have in enhancing or hindering its arrival.<p> 

Earlier in the year, PFF, in conjunction with <a href="/townhall/clubs_groups/cse/cse.html">Citizens for a Sound Economy</a>, <a href="/heritage">The
Heritage Foundation</a>, <a href="gopher://gopher.seattle.wa.us:70/11ftp%3AGopher%3A%20%20Seattle%20USA%20Yellow%20Pages%3AInternational%20Affairs%3ADiscovery%20Institute%3A">The Discovery Institute</a> and the <a href="gopher://nuinfo.nwu.edu:70/00/graduate/dissertation/Hudson%20Institute">Hudson Institute</a>, hosted a
congressional seminar on "Updating the Communications Act: The Free Market
Approach." Held in the Capitol Building on January 31, 1995, In excess of seventy
Members of <A HREF="http://thomas.loc.gov/home/thomas.html">Congress</A> as well key staff and media, including <a href="http://www.wsj.com">The Wall Street
Journal</a> and <a href="http://ibd.ensemble.com/">Investor's Business Daily</a>, attended the seminar.<p>

<i>For more information contact: <a href="mailto:JLee@pff.org">JLee@pff.org</a>.</i><p>



<center>
<a href="/pff/i-fcc.html"><img alt="Replace the FCC" border=0 src="/pff/multi/gif/bt-fcc.gif"></a>
<a href="/pff/i-cyber.html"><img alt="The Nature of Cyberspace" border=0 src="/pff/multi/gif/bt-cyber.gif"></a><br>
<a href="/pff/i-info.html"><img alt="The Meaning of the Information Age" border=0 src="/pff/multi/gif/bt-info.gif"></a>
<a href="/pff/vlahos_summit.html"><img alt="The Big Change" border=0 src="/pff/multi/gif/bt-chnge.gif"></a><br> 

