<HEAD>
<title>Surfing the Sheraton. The Internet Society Summit in San Diego. 
 -- PFF</title>


</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<H1>Surfing the Sheraton.<br> 
The Internet Society Summit in San Diego.</H1>

<P>By Mike Vlahos, Senior Fellow, The Progress & Freedom Foundation 

<P><A HREF="http://www.nosc.mil/planet_earth/sandiego.html">San Diego</A> is not
just another pretty place promising azure sky by day, and
cobalt
by night. It is first, the Navy's town: the city itself looks small, like it is
doing homage to the gray shapes of steel that look bigger as they pass the
channel between the city and Coronado, burling by with the immense stateliness
that comes from moving without the appearance of velocity. 

<P>Steel. Manufacturing. Industrial Age imagery in charge. This is the antithesis
of
ether: sun glinting off missile box launchers and guns, like it must have off the
battleship gray hulls of Task Force 58 50 years ago, steam up and on to Okinawa.

<P>But the internet is all contrast: jewel-like graphics shimmering digitally off
the faces of a new elite, seeking darkness in place of light: their odyssey not
there in South Pacific heat, but here, in the cool confections of cyberspace.

<P>Flying in yesterday, that was the contrast I expected, a sharp thematic cut
between old and new, past and future.

<P>I found something different. And ordinary. 


<P>The Crowd.

<P>Fewer pony tails than I expected, and so many of them gray! No, this was a
true
multi-cultural gathering, a Diet of WWW conclave with equal measures of 

<P><A NAME="typea"> suit and tie, pony tail optional</A> [Type A]  <A NAME="typeb">chinos, white socks</A> [Type B]
 <A NAME="typebplus">jeans, ersatz lacoste, boat shoes</A> [Type B+] 
<A NAME="typebplusplus">whiteshirtpotbellyspillingoverthefadedjeans</A> [Type B++],  <A NAME="typec">the babybluesweater and
mustache look</A> [Type C]  <A NAME="typecplus">the big beard, balding, v-neck</A> [Type C+]  <A NAME="typed">relaxed
Japanese cyber-egged-on oxymoron</A> [Type D]  <A NAME="typee">Pinstripe suit and Aussie mid-back
hair, coifed</A> [Type E]  <A NAME="typef">Euro-neat short hair, suit optional</A> [Type F] 

<P>[And by the way, all the women were wearing suits] 

<P>There was exactly one journalist [<http://sfgate.com/new/schron/index.cgi">San Francisco Chronicle</A>] hooked up to and
using
a computer. Only three others were using them, in an audience of about 100, and
one of them is Cerf himself [after his speech]; oh, and an <A HREF="http://www.hp.com/">HP</A> palmtop too.
EVERYBODY ELSE IS TAKING HAND-NOTES. 


<P>The Kick-Off.

<P><A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Vint Cerf</A> --
like bad novels liked to say -- was resplendent in thin-pin
Statedept. togs, truly lungfish-sartorial in a world of dockers. 

<P>It's 8:00 AM, and it is slowly hitting me: the incredible ordinariness of the
setting. Here is the future, measured and packaged in a neural-numbing hotel box
... burned-out holly-print carpeting, ersatz Louis Quinze partitions, sweet
cheese Danish, silver plate pitchers of half-and-half bathed in condensation,
matching holly-leaf dome chandeliers set into cheap acoustic tiles: all the charm
of interior anachronism elevated to a kind of ultimate fin de siecle American
mixed metaphor ... 

<P>It could have been a gala New Avenues in Hemorrhoid delivery, or the big
convention of the Postal Deliverers' Reform Foundation, or the annual meeting
of the Association of Hickory-Smoked Wood Putty Manufacturers. But it wasn't.

<P>It was the <A HREF="http://www.isoc.org">Internet Society</A> Summit [oh, how
the mighty (word) has fallen!],
and
here was a darkened room with a screen set up in one corner; you know, the kind
we stared at during death march slide shows in first grade. And yes, he's showing
slides. Well, at least they're from a computer LCD on an overhead projector, and
not good old petroleum slides. 

<P>And the droning is traditional too: I have vivid memories of showing up at
that
place when they first inaugurated .... Well, to be fair, it is the first
session, and, like a good Victorian play, the maid does have to get onstage and
give the essential exposition. 

<P>But it's deja vu all over again. Same as Atlanta [but better, brighter
colors]:
WWW started in 89, led to Mosaic ... blah blah left <A
HREF="http://www.sgi.com">Silicon Graphics</A> and founded
<A HREF="http://home.netscape.com">Netscape</A>, luring away blah blah blah ... 

<P>Now I get it: <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf's</A> reliving the good ole days, the glory days, when men were
men and heroes walked the earth. He doesn't see what he's doing either: 

<P><A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A> is denying change in the Internet's culture, its way of life, while at
the
same time trumpeting its coming dominion. He mixes nostalgia and sentimental
memory [as did all the older speakers, a hand-picked, band of brothers, all at
Agincourt] with the paean of explosive growth. 

<P>Begin a litanic recitation of glorious stats [so with every speaker: the
same].
It was like an after-dinner testimonial [from modest beginnings ... , from a log
cabin ... , with only three dollars in his pocket ...] 

<P>A pocketful of miracles reduced to magical decimals: 

<P> 4,851,000 on the net
 94 countries wired [what's a country?]  growing at 9-12% a month
 200,000,000 plugged-in by end of decade  50,000 networks
 research: 27%
 commercial: 53% and growing [so what else is new?]  education: 5%
 govt.: 10%
 military: 7%
 and this, in 93
[available on <A HREF="http://www.isoc.org">internet society web page</A>] 

<P>The whole world will be plugged in for the millennium! 


<P>He went on:

<P> Growth in world faster than in US [duhhh ...]  Fr. and UK fastest in Eur.
 Aus. Jap. Taiwan biggest surge in E Asia  And gee, high positive correlation
between internet growth and high 
GNP [duhhh ... maybe we need a govt. study] 

<P>Then he offers the potentially useful thought that over time, more internet
means
more income -- but then he let's it drop! [He doesn't want to push the internet
as key to a global economic revolution. Too much change? Change the internet out
of recognition, maybe? Got a whiff of grapeshot there, Vint.]

<P>He enjoys this metaphor far more: <A
HREF="http://peacock.tnjc.edu.tw/ROC_info.html">Taiwan</A> -- they make 88% of
all PC
motherboards. Golly, if they kept some of them, instead of exporting them, maybe
their income would go up! [I thought their income was going up, through the
roof, precisely because they were exporting the damn things!] 

<P>Acerbic on <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A>; Mea culpa, I can't help it. <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A> was in the weeds of the web:
his worries are all about how to keep it open, how to keep it civil, how to keep
the good uses going, and limit the encroachment of the bad [like govt.
restrictions on free speech, which he sees as too hard for old order govts. to do
anyway. (But see my talk with <A HREF="http://www.singnet.com.sg/singnet/singtel/singtel.html">Singapore Telecom</A>, and get a nice cold spritz!)]

<P>And then, someone raised the spectre of The Nefarious One: What about
<A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft</A>
monopolization? <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A>: won't happen, because other services can spring up if
<A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft</A> overcharges [Overcharges!!!!!!!! Give me a Pharonic Break!]

<P>And then, someone gushes that the net will bring us true democracy -- Not so,
says <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A>. He says, what happens when you have 100,000 E-mail messages flooding
in at once: No one could deal with that; we must engage our brains to deal with
scaling problem.

<P>See what I mean? To <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A> -- and the whole succeedent summit tenor of thought
--
all issues involve making the net work better as it is now, as The Internet.

<P>Example: The net must stay ill-defined to escape regulation [<A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A> wants to
keep
the feel of the old net ethos]. 

<P>Then a Euro-wimp whines: The US controls all the net technology; therefore,
the
US can control everyone else who uses the net [Is it still 1968?] 

<P><A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf's</A> retort to this starts off better: supplier companies have a global
perspective, they want to sell (half of their business outside of US, they are
motivated to keep their business base in world). But then on to Big Al: 
The Nat. Information Infrastructure must match global needs; unless we make it
uniform, it is useless--that is direction I see on policy side [Gee whiz, Ma! So
there is an NII after all!].


<P>Morning Panel -- Administrative Infrastructure. 

<P>There are four speakers. The first speaker is a <a href="#typecplus">Type C+</A> -- sweater-wire-rims
plus
full beard and pony, all gray, of course -- Aquinas discoursing on internet names
[domain names], protocols, IP address allocation [credibility, fairness,
routing--we're going to run out! so now it's a control thing] 

<P>Wow!

<P>And he's using petroleum slides! Other parameters: port numbers, protocol
numbers
-- assigned by the internet numbers authority 

<P>[It's called a summit, but some still ask questions like What's the Internet?]

<P>Next speaker's a <a href="#typebplusplus">Type B++</a> in masquerade -- he's got on a blue blazer, and
apologizes, lamely. He's a Registration Services Man, and excited about his work
-- Boy, it's lighting the ether on fire! There is an E-mail explosion going on --
how to handle it? [my SCO system is broken, how do I fix it?] 

<P>And on and on it goes: how to handle domain demand at hundreds a day? ..edu,
.net
not growing, .comm, also .org [from small base] are the big burners.

<P>Perhaps it's in the lineage, the bloodlines, the genes; but this jargon makes
Pentagonese argot taste sweet on an English tongue: 

<P>CIDR ization of INADDR.ARPA
Rollout of SWIP

<P>Our resources are stressed!

<P>Next speaker's <a href="#typebplusplus">Type B++</a>, whiteshirtpotbellyspillingoverthefadedjeans, with two
first names, and he's the guy in charge of naming. 

<P>This guy's also stuck on petro-slides, but he goes one better: they're
colorless
[making him ante-ante-diluvian] He's covering Asia, so it's all Pac-argot: 

<P>a peer of <A HREF="http://www.internic.net">InterNIC</A>, RIPE-NCC
ISPs are APNICs most important customers org. IANA, regional Irs
Whois database, WAIS database, DNS database, etc. 

<P>[at least etc. makes sense, I like that database] 

<P>Next guy from Neth., screaming Madras cotton shirt and shooort hair <a href="#typef">[Type F]</a>
and
the only guy there with a bona fide backpack [up on the podium!]. At least his
petroleum jargon gives better names -- <A HREF="http://www.ripe.net/">RIPE</A> (forum of providers), <A HREF="http://www.terena.nl/">TERENA</A> (the
assoc. of research networks), and <A HREF="http://www.ebone.net/">EBONE</A> [not a clue!], all hinting at more
elite-oriented interest in the internet in among the euro-wimps. This guy speaks
better English than Henry Kissinger; it's the words themselves that convey no
meaning -- outside the charmed nomenclatura that are the Internetski.

<P>Then he says it all: you need qualified engineers; you need nerds. Nuff
said.

<P>ALL HAVE 2-D LINE/CURVE CHARTS AS CENTERPIECE FOR THEIR GRAPHICS [only <A HREF="http://astrowww.phys.uvic.ca/a200/creators.html">Cerf</A>
has
snazzy 3-D stuff, slick as his spotted red silk tie]] 

<P>Providers in euro-land from beginning to end 1995: 32 to 250! [see, more of
the
stat-opiate]
[later, I find out all numbers at the conference bogus, unsubstantiated] [I also
find out, from a Swiss AG, that German telecom I-net hook up and use rates three
times that of La Suisse, which are tres high, but of course! So much for access!]

<P>Last guy a lawyer, all-darkman guido suit and open shirt, heavy jowls, Big
Brother mustache [untyped in this sub-culture]. Big Shoulder City's top firm, but
he's trying to look caj here. You know, the half-poly knit with the little
MacDonalds heraldry on the left tit. 

<P>He is representing the international trademark assoc.; and finally, things get
interesting. He addresses the big worries of the gathering of techno-geeks:

<P>Are domain names trademarks or not?

<P>Domain names represent registered trademarks, he says, and do tell the story
of
the Newsday reporter who took McDonald's as his domain name, with Ronald as his
personal moniker. He graciously gave it up for a donation by BigMac to his fav
charity, but the BigMo is on. 

<P>There's a guy out there with the domain name, Coke, and he's holding CC ransom
for big$. The US patent office regards domain names as being capable of being
trademarks. The issue: is it used as TM, in trade [unlike a phone number]?
[there's another guy I know about who's going around gathering domain names for
every city in Mass.]

<P>Yes, it's Wild West time on the WWW. And it gets worse. 

<P>There's a co. called knowledgenet reg. Well it seems that another company
registered same as its domain name. Now there's a lawsuit, complaint, as well as
infringement and restraint of trade ... and even RICO! What do the doyens of the
internet do? Publish requests for domain names, turn over to govt.? Right. That
one really took off. Boos and hisses. 

<P>But what is interesting here is the emotional subtext beneath the surface
talk.
These guys are scared; their beloved net is being defiled by trade, yet commerce
is making it the world of tomorrow! To reach the stars, they lose control. They
lose the Internet itself. 


<P>Luncheon Buzz

<P>Now for the real talk; like, a journalist from <A HREF="http://www.ziff.com">Ziff</A> [<A HREF="http://www.ziff.com:8002/~pcweek/">PC Week</A>] talking about
her
frequency. What she meant was that she was now competing, not with other
zines, but with the likes of the Wall Street Journal web page, and Ziff wanted
more and more from her, because they have to post everyday on their web page [the
real virtual sweatshop, ladies & gentlemen, begins here]. 

<P>Also, what about all those millions of providers? All morning speakers gushed
like founts about providers like shooting-star Roman Candles. The Chaos of the
Internet forever!

<P>But then, <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft</A> is inundated with requests for its new portal: <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com/pages/services/msnet/msnintro.html">Microsoft
Network</A>. Embedded; this is the word. It is embedded in its operating system, and
especially in the application bundle that everyone uses, Microsoft Office. Like
its purchase of Intuit, <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft</A> stands to dominate, not because, as suggested
wrongly earlier, Gates will overcharge, but because he will make it easy and
cheap to connect, to get all the services you want, and to do it all from within
Word [<A HREF="http://www.qdeck.com/">Quarterdeck</A>, in fact, has just come out with a patch for <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com/pages/deskapps/word/wordhome.html">Word 6.0</A> that lets
you send and receive, cruise the net, 
all from within <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com/pages/deskapps/word/wordhome.html">Word</A>].

<P>What is about to happen, in other words, is that the thousands of providers
just
plain collapse in the next few years. The few big coalitions, the ones that can
come up with the capital to build the interface, offer the services, and make it
easy within the desktop environment, and make it more and more like an appliance,
will be the ones who catch the market surge of the hoi polloi. It's Railroad
Baron Byte City building. And the old internet is dead.

<P><A HREF="http://www.singnet.com.sg/singnet/singtel/singtel.html">Singapore Telecom</A> guy insists that govt. doesn't care, isn't listening in; 
but that Lee Quan et al freaked out when they were told that there were 3000
unlicensed bulletin boards on the island! And now, get this, the govt. has
created the first national web site, the <A HREF="http://www.sg">Singapore Home Page</A>. And [are we
surprised?] everybody in Singapore posts there. And guess who's listening? 
[Kishore Mahbubani, Sing's perm foreign secretary , told me We don't want
America's decadence, but (to control) there are other alternatives to Pravda]


<P>Afternoon Panel: The Internet in commerce 

<P>Another member of the Old Guard. And gleaning gets hard. Real hard. 

<P>One pale anecdote after another [when I was creating ARPAbucks in 1978 ...] 

<P>One good insight:
[maybe]
in private internets, sloppy works
in public internets, sloppy fails

<P>[Why did I like this? I have spent the past two nights trying to launch into
the
net, without success. Oh, I get on, after about ten or fifteen minutes of SLIPing
and PINGing. Each time. Then, it's all so slow I feel I could live out my life
waiting for a search to finish. And I've got a 28.8 modem! 
Right now, it's a mess; a toy]

<P>As for the rest, blah, blah, blah:

<P>Gee, we'll all be doing our shopping on the net Gee, no more paper money
Gee, no more banks

<P>[But it's still that same old, lovable net] 

<P>Why is there nothing about the real future, where the internet is going, not
even
for the next three to five years? This is a summit in the weeds, down in the
rushes by the floodplain: what do we do about this, what do we do about that?

<P>They're truly clueless; reliving past triumphs, in at the creation, original
and
authentic members of Hal's band of brothers ... 

<P>So it went on. The second afternoon speaker passeth all understanding: 

<P>BOF and IESG plenary,
temporary IETF area formed to consolidate Ipng activity; then, RFC1550 call for
papers

<P>[What?!]
[here's a hint: ALE is address lifetime expectations] 

<P>By the way, did you know that the IP version six-header has a payload?
packets,
payloads, mapping, addresses, routing; it's all antique imagery, like bulletin
boards, web pages, WWW yellow pages ... 

<P>Say it again,

<P>These are the digital groveling at the altar of Guttenburg, or, 

<P>15th century new wave.

<P>Lord, they know not what they have, they know even less what to do with it,
and
they know yet less than that about where it's going. These summiteers are in
NOT land, as in Byte City. NOT!

<P>Two days at the summit, and not one panel on where we are going. It's internet
Geek World forever; it just gets better and better, and in the end, we all
become, yes, you guessed it,<p> 

WWW Geeks too.<br>
M. Vlahos.<br>
12 April, 1995<br>
