<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>The Dissent of Man</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<BLOCKQUOTE><B>From July 20, 1996 <I>TheWall Street Journal</I>, p. A13</B></BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><BR>
<BR>
</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H1>The dissent of man</H1>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3><I>A review of Darwin's Black Box, by Michael Behe<BR>
by Paul R. Gross</I></H3>
<IMG SRC="newbar.gif" WIDTH="374" HEIGHT="10" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"><BR>
Decades after the infamous Scopes Trial, the debate over Darwinism is<BR>
heating up again, even among Darwinists. For them, however, the debate is<BR>
merely over details of the standard model. The truly brazen challenges to<BR>
Darwinian thought come from creationists--mostly religious believers who
read<BR>
Genesis literally and believe all species to have been created one-by-one
and<BR>
for a purpose. But creationism, too, has internal rivals.<BR>
<BR>
The fanciest version of creationism does not contest the brute facts<BR>
of geology and organic evolution' it concedes the immense age of the planet<BR>
and allows that evolution happens, at least within species. But it rejects
the<BR>
mechanisms--one of which is Darwin's natural selection--by which scientists<BR>
generally say evolutionary change occurs. This form of creationism--called<BR>
Intelligent Design Theory--argues that mere &quot;chance&quot; couldn't
make anything so<BR>
obviously &quot;designed&quot; as the human eye, let alone life. If life
is designed,<BR>
there must be a designer, no?<BR>
<BR>
The argument isn't new. Design is a common theme in medieval proofs of<BR>
the existence of God. William Paley's Divine Watchmaker--the Creator--was<BR>
believed throughout the 19th century (even by some Darwinists) to be required<BR>
by the complexity of life. But for scientists concerned with the study of<BR>
evolution, &quot;<A HREF="bydesign.html">intelligent design</A>&quot; ceased
to be taken seriously about 100 years<BR>
ago.<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="behe.html">Michael J. Behe</A>, associate professor of biochemistry
at Lehigh<BR>
University, thinks he has rehabilitated the argument. In &quot;Darwin's
Black Box&quot;<BR>
(Free Press, 307 pages, $25), he claims to refute not simply old-fashioned<BR>
Darwinism but the 20th-century synthesis of paleontology, anatomy, embryology<BR>
and molecular genetics--what might be called Neo-Darwinism. According to<BR>
Neo-Darwinism, the diversity of life results from the survival of hereditary<BR>
variations that arise by chance at the level of genes--that is, at the level<BR>
of chemistry.<BR>
<BR>
Mr. Behe tries hard to avoid the theistic platitudes of &quot;creation<BR>
science.&quot; he insists that &quot;inferences to design do not require
that we have a<BR>
candidate for the role of designer.&quot; He will not force God on his<BR>
readers--just a designer. So &quot;Darwin's Black Box&quot; includes a popular
tour of<BR>
some molecular processes at the cellular level of life. That much is<BR>
unexceptionable and well-written.<BR>
<BR>
But there is a key argument: The &quot;black box&quot; of the cell has now
been<BR>
opened by science (true enough). It is not simple (also true). The complexity<BR>
of whole organisms SEEMS modest compared with the complexity of their cellular<BR>
chemistry. So, he asks, could that complexity have happened step-by-step,<BR>
gradually, as Darwin proposed? No way, he answers; not unless the molecular<BR>
designs were already built in! The chemistry of life is just too complex
to<BR>
have come about &quot;by chance.&quot; In his own words: &quot;As the number
of required<BR>
parts increases, the difficulty of gradual putting the system together<BR>
skyrockets, and the likelihood of indirect scenarios plummets. Darwin looks<BR>
more and more forlorn.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But no more now than before is this convincing. Natural selection does<BR>
not operate &quot;by chance&quot; in any ordinary sense. Changes in the
genes do arise<BR>
randomly: This has been documented as well as anything in science. But there<BR>
is nothing chancy about what happens next, which is the survival and increase<BR>
of what WORKS. Nor is it true that as the number of required parts increases<BR>
&quot;the difficulty of gradually putting the system together skyrockets.&quot;
In fact,<BR>
complex systems--think of modern cities--CAN and DO assemble gradually rather<BR>
than all at once. Darwinism does not require complexity to arise willy-nilly<BR>
from simple parts. It requires only an adequate pool of variations in existing<BR>
parts, a changing environment and time for particular variations to increase<BR>
or die out in the population.<BR>
<BR>
Of late, the most notorious example of this process is the newly<BR>
drug-resistant bacteria and viruses that take over in an antibiotic-rich<BR>
environment. These are life-forms with novel chemistries, &quot;selected&quot;
from<BR>
continuous random changes in the genes: These genes make altered proteins,<BR>
which cause changes in chemistry and eventually a new form of life. With<BR>
viruses, this happens with alarming speed. Old kinds go extinct and new
kinds<BR>
take over within days. In higher, multicellular species, although the time<BR>
frame may be longer, the sources of molecular variations are the same or
even<BR>
more abundant and environmental pressures are just as severe if not more
so.<BR>
In sum: The evidence for old chemistry modifying to serve new purposes in<BR>
systems of increasing complexity is overwhelming.<BR>
<BR>
Unfortunately, Mr. Behe patronizes or ignores the successes of<BR>
molecular evolution and pounces on a few puzzles as though each spelled
the<BR>
death of Darwinism. He does not attend seriously to the developmental<BR>
consequences of small genetic changes, which create whole new body-plans.
Thus<BR>
&quot;Darwin's Black Box&quot; is not the refutation of Darwinism that creationists
long<BR>
for. Science cannot yet explain, among other things, the origin of life
on<BR>
this planet a few billion years ago. But whatever happened then, there is
no<BR>
trace--at least in the findings of science so far--of an intelligent designer<BR>
intervening thereafter.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><I>Mr. Gross is university professor of life sciences, emeritus, at
the<BR>
University of Virginia.</I></H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
