<HEAD>
<TITLE>Appendices -- PFF</TITLE>
<boDY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
</HEAD>


<h1>APPENDICES:</h1>
<br><p><br><p>
To return to the previous page, please use your browser's back feature.
<hr>


<CENTER><h2>APPENDIX 1  </h2></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>DEFINITIONS OF TERMS AND ABBREVIATIONS
<BR>
 </B></CENTER>
<P>
<B>Affiliate </B>
- a company owned by a holding company 
<P>
<B>Affiliate transactions </B>
- transactions between companies within a single holding company
system 
<P>
<B>Disco </B> - distribution
company 
<P>
<B>EHC </B> - exempt
holding company 
<P>
<B>Electric utility company </B>
- any company which owns or operates facilities used for the generation,
transmission or distribution of electric energy for sale, other
than sale to tenants or employees of the company operating such
facilities for their own use  
<P>
<B>EPAct </B> - Energy
Policy Act of 1992 
<P>
<B>EWG </B> - exempt
wholesale generator 
<P>
<B>Exempt holding company </B>
- holding company that is exempt from major provisions of PUHCA
because it complies with statutory exemptions (the most important
ones are that the company's operations are limited to a single
state and that the parent company is predominantly a utility) 
<P>
<B>Exempt wholesale generator </B>
- class of generators, producing electricity for resale, established
by EPAct. Acquisition of these generators by holding companies
is exempt from most provisions of PUHCA.  
<P>
<B>FERC </B> - Federal
Energy Regulatory Commission 
<P>
<B>Gas utility company  </B>-
company that owns or operates facilities used to distribute gas
at retail 
<P>
<B>Genco </B> - generation
company 
<P>
<B>Integration requirement </B>
- provision of PUHCA that requires registered holding companies
to be limited to a single interconnected utility system 
<P>
<B>Pool </B> - centralized
market institution in which electric power is traded through the
process of matching bids from buyers and offers from sellers 
<P>
<B>Public utility company </B>
- electric utility company or gas utility company 
<P>
<B>PUHCA </B> - Public
Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 
<P>
<B>PURPA </B> - Public
Utility Regulatory Policy Act of 1978 
<P>
<B>Registered holding company </B>
- any company that acquires more than 10 percent of the equity
of a utility and, as a consequence, must register with SEC under
PUHCA unless it gains an exemption. RHC is subject to all provisions
of PUHCA 
<P>
<B>Retail wheeling </B>
- transmission and distribution of electric power from the generator
to the consumer through lines owned by other entities 
<P>
<B>RHC </B> - registered
holding company 
<P>
<B>SEC </B> - Securities
and Exchange Commission 
<P>
<B>Transco </B> -
transmission company 
<P>
<B>Unbundling </B>
- separation of generation, transmission and distribution functions
of a utility. Unbundling can take many forms, from keeping separate
accounts for these functions to creating separate corporate entities. 
<P>
<B>Utility holding company </B>
- any company which directly or indirectly owns, controls or holds
with the power to vote, 10 per centum or more of the outstanding
voting securities of a public utility.<BR>
 
<P><br><p>
<CENTER><h2>APPENDIX 2 </h2></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>THE MAIN PROVISIONS OF PUHCA<BR>
 </B></CENTER>
<P>
The main provisions of PUHCA are summarized
below. A &quot;holding company&quot; is a company that owns ten
percent or more of the voting stock of a &quot;public utility
company.&quot; <a href="foot.html"><sup>65</sup></a> 
A &quot;public utility company&quot; is an electric
or gas utility company.  An electric or gas utility is any company
which owns or operates facilities to generate, transmit (in the
case of electricity) or distribute (in either case) these goods
for sale.  Numerous activities undertaken by public utilities
are regulated under PUHCA.  These can be divided into several
main areas:<BR>
 
<P>
<u>1) Registration </u>.
 As discussed above, all utility holding companies must either
register under the Act or seek an exemption.  Section 2 of the
Act requires that any firm acquiring more than 10 percent of the
equity of a utility must register as a holding company.<BR>
 
<P>
<U>2) Exemption </u>.
 The Act creates two main categories of public utility holding
companies: &quot;registered&quot; holding companies and &quot;exempt&quot;
holding companies.  Registered holding companies (RHC's) are subject
to all provisions of the Act, while exempt holding companies (EHC's)
are exempt from critical provisions of the Act.  There are currently
fourteen registered holding companies in the U.S.<BR>
 
<P>
There are several ways a holding company can
gain an exemption from the Act.  There are technically five statutory
exemptions.  The two main ones are, first, if a holding company's
operations are predominantly within a single state (i.e., &quot;intrastate&quot;
- Section 3 (a)(1)) and second, if the parent company is &quot;predominantly
a utility&quot; (Section 3 (a)(2)) meaning that the parent is
itself predominantly an operating utility, and operations of the
holding company system are limited to the state in which the parent
is organized, and contiguous states.<a href="foot.html"><sup>66</sup></a>  
The three remaining exemptions
are if the holding company is &quot;only incidentally a holding
company,&quot; a &quot;temporary holding company,&quot; or a &quot;foreign
holding company.&quot; <BR>
 
<P>
<U>3) Issuance and Acquisition of Securities </U>
(Sections 6 and 7).  The Act also regulates the securities and
assets that a registered holding company or its subsidiaries can
hold.  These sections make it unlawful to issue or sell a security
without prior SEC approval.  Specifically, the Act requires that
a security be &quot;reasonably adapted&quot; to the earning power
and security structure of the issuing company and to the capital
structure of the company, among other requirements. <BR>
 
<P>
<U>4) Acquisition of Utility Interests </U>
(Sections 8, 9 and 10).  These sections affect the acquisition
of securities, utility assets, and interests in other businesses.
 Section 8 prohibits a registered holding company from owning
an electric utility and a gas utility without the approval of
the state commission.  Section 9 places restrictions on the type
of assets that can be acquired.  It prohibits registered holding
companies from acquiring any securities, utility assets or any
other interest in any business (unless approved by the SEC) under
the standards of Section 10. Additionally, this section prohibits
any person (including both registered and exempt holding companies)
from acquiring any security of any public utility company, if
that purchase makes the person an affiliate (unless approved by
the SEC).  In the so-called &quot;two-bite rule, Section 9(a)(2)
requires that if a company owns five percent of a utility, transaction
that would result in ownership of more than 5 percent of the equity
of another utility requires prior SEC approval.<BR>
 
<P>
<U>5) Simplification of Holding Company Systems </U>
(Section 11).  An important goal of the Act was to integrate and
simplify the holding company system.  Section 11(b)(1) of the
Act requires that each registered holding company be limited to
a single &quot;integrated public-utility system,&quot; (although
the SEC has the authority to relax this constraint).  This essentially
limits the RHC to a particular geographic region and thus fosters
local control.  Non-utility businesses can be acquired only if
they are &quot;reasonably incidental, or economically necessary
or appropriate&quot; to the operations of the integrated utility
system, as defined in the Act.<BR>
 
<P>
<U>6) Coordination with State Regulatory Authorities </U>.
 An additional goal of the Act was to facilitate regulation of
public utilities on the state level.  For example, Section 6(b)
authorizes the SEC to exempt the issuance of certain securities
by subsidiary companies if approved by a state commission.  Likewise,
Section 9(b) exempts some asset acquisitions from provisions of
Section 10 if approved by a state commission.  Moreover, the SEC
may not authorize the issuance of securities or the acquisition
of assets unless the applicant has complied with state laws.<BR>
 
<P>
<U>7) Intercompany Transactions </U>
(Section 12).  This section was intended to limit transactions
between various affiliates within the holding company system.
 For example, section 12 (a) states that RHC's may not borrow
or receive any extension of credit or indemnity from any system
utility company.  Additionally, the SEC was given rule-making
authority over a large number of other affiliate transactions,
such as use of loans, payments of dividends, and disposal of assets.
<BR>
 
<P>
<U>8) Service Company Regulation </U>
(Section 13).  This section of the Act regulates contracts between
operating companies and service companies.  For example, Section
13 (b) states that service, sales, and construction contracts
between system companies in the same holding company system must
be performed &quot;economically and efficiently for the benefit
of such associate companies at cost, fairly, and equitably allocated
among such companies.&quot; <BR>
 
<P>
<U>9) Reports and Accounts </U>
(Sections 14 and 15).  These sections require RHCs to file routine
reports and keep record in accordance with the SEC's requirements.
<BR>
 
<P>
 <U>10) Exemptions since PURPA</U>.  There
are two main ways that these restrictions under PUHCA have been
alleviated since its passage.  First, under the Public Utility
Regulatory Policies Act (PURPA) of 1978, &quot;qualifying facilities&quot;
under that Act were exempted from PUHCA.  Second, The Gas Related
Activities Act of 1990<a href="foot.html"><sup>67</sup></a>
 allows gas utility holding companies to
seek exemption from PUHCA for certain activities including gas
transportation, storage and acquisitions related to gas supply.
Third, the Energy Policy Act of 1992 amended PUHCA in order to
create an exemption for exempt wholesale generators, which are
essentially facilities devoted exclusively to the generation of
electricity exclusively for sale on the wholesale level.  This
act also created an exemption for foreign utility companies, which
allows an RHC to own a foreign utility.  However, numerous aspects
of these transactions are still regulated by the SEC. 
<P><br><p>
<CENTER><h2>APPENDIX 3 </h2></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>SUMMARY OF RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES
IN SELECTED STATES<BR>
 </B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>California </B></CENTER>
<P>
Public Utility Commission's (PUC) December
20, 1995 Restructuring Decision:  Orders retail wheeling and poolco
market structure starting Jan 1998.  All customers would be eligible
by 1999, or by 2003 if there are technical problems.  Bilaterals
will be allowed, but at the beginning, all IOU's will be required
to buy and sell all their power through the Power Exchange, which
would gradually become a voluntary spot market.  Transmission
system operated by an independent system operator (ISO) according
to information from bilaterals and Power Exchange.  Both ISO and
Power Exchange should be FERC-regulated, independent of transmitters
and generators.  100 percent of stranded costs allowed to be recovered
through a non-bypassable (i.e. paid by all customers) competition
transition charge (CTC), but at a lower rate of return.  SCE and
PG&amp;E required to file plans to voluntarily divest themselves
of at least 50 percent of their fossil generation to a non-affiliated
entity because of market power concerns. <BR>
 
<P>
<CENTER><B>Massachusetts </B></CENTER>
<P>
On May 1, 1996 the Department of Public Utilities
(DPU) issued draft restructuring rules.  The rules envision implementation
of retail wheeling beginning 1998, a Power Exchange as a market
for short-term power sales, an ISO, separation of generation,
transmission and distribution into distinct corporate entities
and stranded costs recovery over ten years through a non-bypassable
access charge. 
<P>
Following DPU's request of August 1995, the
Division of Energy Resources and five (5) utilities have filed
their own restructuring plans, all of them presuming retail wheeling
and most of them proposing the separation or divestiture of generation
assets as the right way to mitigate market power and calculate
stranded costs. 
<P>
A number of bills on retail wheeling for manufactures
and municipal aggregation of loads are pending but not expected
to pass before DPU's final general rules, which are scheduled
for September 1996.  The company-specific orders are to be issued
February and March 1997.   
<P>
DPU imposed the first retail stranded costs
tariff on MIT who built a PURPA 20MW cogeneration facility and
hence departed from Cambridge Electric Light Co.  The tariff provides
for recovery of 75 percent of associated stranded costs. <BR>
 
<P>
<CENTER><B>New Hampshire </B></CENTER>
<P>
The Public Utility Commission issued final
guidelines for a two-year retail wheeling pilot program (starting
May 1996) and applicable to about 50MW.  Participation is open
to any supplier who in turn must obtain NEPOOL membership or contract
with a NEPOOL member.  Utilities, except for individually negotiated
plans, will be allowed to recover 50 percent of stranded costs.
 
<P>
Both House and Senate passed a bill requiring
the PUC to order retail wheeling by June 1998 for all customer
classes.  The bill is expected to be signed by the Governor. 
It leaves the decision over the degree of unbundling to the PUC.
 It also instructs the PUC to assure recovery of nonmitigatable
stranded costs through a time-limited charge to all customers.
 
<P>
On June 6, 1995, the PUC ruled in the Freedom
Energy case that the utility franchise granted to Public Service
of New Hampshire was not exclusive on a permanent basis. <BR>
 
<P>
<CENTER><B>Rhode Island </B></CENTER>
<P>
The Electric Industry Restructuring Collaborative,
established by the PUC and comprised of broad spectrum of stakeholders,
issued an interim progress report, reaching consensus on most
issues, but not on a stranded cost recovery mechanism.  
<P>
A retail wheeling bill was introduced in the
House with New England Electric System's support and is expected
to pass.  The bill calls for gradual implementation of retail
wheeling starting in 1998, functional unbundling into separate
affiliates, and stranded costs recovery by 2009.  
<P>
Subsidiaries of Eastern Utilities Associates
filed a restructuring plan calling for retail wheeling for all
customers starting 1998.  It also contained a recovery of nuclear
stranded cost that would extend until all current obligations
are satisfied.<BR>
 
<P>
<CENTER><B>New York </B></CENTER>
<P>
In December 1995, an administrative law judge
(ALJ) issued a decision in the Public Service Commission's competitive
opportunities case recommending that PSC initiate wholesale competition
through a pool with an ISO and then add retail wheeling as soon
as possible.  Following the decision, the PSC approved a restructuring
plan which calls for creating a wholesale pool in 1997 and implementing
retail wheeling in 1998. While the PSC's plan envisions a system
operator consisting of member utilities and a &quot;green surcharge&quot;
to fund renewable programs, it does not deal with stranded costs
recovery.  
<P>
The PSC is also in the process of reviewing
company-specific restructuring proposals filed by Niagara Mohawk
and Long Island Lighting and ordered remaining five of state's
utilities to file their plans. The New York Power Authority has
proposed becoming an ISO and take over other utilities' transmission.
<BR>
 
<P>
<CENTER><B>Illinois </B></CENTER>
<P>
The Commerce Commission approved a retail wheeling
pilot programs for Central Illinois Light and Illinois Power.
 Both programs are designed primarily for large loads.  Commonwealth
Edison proposed a long-range restructuring framework, consisting
of a five-year rate-freeze for its customers and experimental
five-year retail access starting 1998.  There are several legislative
proposals pending, including those of the Coalition for Consumer
Choice and Central Illinois Public Service.  All proposals presume
some sort of retail wheeling. 
<br><hr><p>
