<HEAD>
<TITLE> INTRODUCTION -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<CENTER><h2>I.  INTRODUCTION </h2></CENTER>

<P>
In sector after sector of the American economy
- from airlines to telecommunications - competition already has
replaced, or is replacing, regulation as the primary market structure.
 This competition revolution is now sweeping into the energy industry.
 Forty-six states are considering introducing competition into
their energy markets, and some Members of Congress are calling
for the complete deregulation of the energy industry. 
<P>
America is home to one-third of all the installed
electric energy capacity in the world, with investor-owned utility
assets in excess of $500 billion and total revenues of the electric
energy industry of $200 billion annually.   Allowing competition
in this industry would provide consumers with billions of dollars
annually in economic benefits and spur the introduction of better
generating technologies. 
<P>
Yet efforts to introduce competition into the
energy industry are hindered by a regulatory hold over from the
Depression.  The Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 is
a major barrier to state reform efforts.  In addition, its primary
purpose - to protect consumers and investors - is better served
by other existing mechanisms. Today, the Act is denying consumers
the benefits of more energy choices at better rates. 
<P>
This paper demonstrates that PUHCA should be
repealed as an important step in bringing the benefits of the
competition revolution to all consumers of energy in America.
 After a brief explanation of the origins and provisions of PUHCA,
the paper explains in section III how the Act is standing in the
way of state competition initiatives. 
<P>
Section IV explores how PUHCA hinders the most
efficient production of energy. Next, the paper explains that
the Act interferes with efficient energy regulation.  Section
VI explains that sixty years after the Depression, PUHCA is redundant.
 Not only has the industry itself transformed, but other federal
government bodies and market mechanisms are better able to protect
consumers and investors. 
<P>
At the end of the paper are appendices defining
terms and abbreviations, outlining the main provisions of PUHCA,
and explaining the reform efforts underway in the leading states. 
<P>
Repealing PUHCA would be a major step forward
in deregulating the energy industry.  It is time to remove this
outdated and redundant regulatory barrier to competition. It is
time to allow the states to experiment with the best methods for
providing consumers with the benefits of energy competition.<BR>
<BR><hr><p>
<center>
