<HEAD>

<TITLE>	REPEALING PUHCA -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a><p>
 June 11, 1996<BR>
<h2> THE COMPETION REVOLUTION AND <br>
 THE MARKET FOR ENERGY:<BR>
THE BENEFITS OF REPEALING THE  <br>
PUBLIC UTILITY HOLDING COMPANY ACT OF 1935<BR></h2>
<BR>

<p>

<CENTER>A White Paper of the<br>
Creating Competitive Markets
in Electric Energy Project<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<h3> Thomas M. Lenard, Ph.D. 
<br>
 R. Richard Geddes, Ph.D. 
<br>
 Michael K. Block, Ph.D.<BR>
</h3>
</center>
<P><br><P>
*The authors gratefully acknowledge
the assistance of Libor Dusek. <BR>
 
<P><br><p><br><p>
<b>Creating Competitive Markets in Electric
Energy Project </b>
<br>
As competition sweeps into America's
energy industry, the crucial public policy issue is, especially
at the federal level, how to restructure the rules of the game
so as to make the most of the current opportunity.  The Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation is undertaking the design of a replacement
model to create a vastly more competitive electricity market to
replace the current legacy of Progressive Era regulations.<BR>
<BR>
 
<P>
<B>Creating Competitive Markets in Electric
Energy Advisory Committee* </B>
<TABLE border="1">

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Henry Manne, Chair 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Dean, School of Law 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>George Mason University 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Robert Crandall 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Senior Fellow, Economic Studies 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>Brookings Institution 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Harold Demsetz 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Professor of Economics 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>University of California, Los Angeles 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>C. Boyden Gray 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Partner </TD>
<TD WIDTH=303>Wilmer, Cutler &amp; Pickering 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Kenneth Gordon 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Senior Vice President 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>National Economic Research Associates 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Luis Guiterrez 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Senior Energy Economist 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>World Bank 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Paul Joskow 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Professor of Economics 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>Massachusetts Institute of Technology 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Craig Lucas 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>General Partner 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>Zimmer Lucas Partners 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>George Schreiber 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Managing Director 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>Paine Webber, Inc. 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>C. Dukes Scott 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Commissioner 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>South Carolina Public Service Commission 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Roger Sherman 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Professor of Economics 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>University of Virginia 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Linda Stuntz 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Partner </TD>
<TD WIDTH=303>Stuntz &amp; Davis 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Branko Terzic 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Chairman, President &amp; CEO 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>Yankee Energy System, Inc. 
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=156>Robert Tollison 
</TD><TD WIDTH=238>Director, Center for the Study of Public Choice 
</TD><TD WIDTH=303>George Mason University 
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
* Members of the Advisory Committee
provide advice and are not responsible for the specific content
of this publication.  Institutional affiliation is given for identification
purposes only.<BR>
<BR>
<p><br> 
<P>
<B>The Competition Revolution and the
Market for Energy: 
The Benefits of Repealing the Public
Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 </B>
<br><p>
Thomas M. Lenard, Ph.D., Senior Fellow,<br>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation 
<p>
R. Richard Geddes, Ph.D., Assistant
Professor of Economics,<br> Fordham University 
<p>
Michael K. Block, Ph.D., Senior Fellow,<br>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation 
<p>
Libor Dusek, Research Fellow,<br> The Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation<BR>
<p>
<hr>
<P>
<font size=2>Future Insight, <i>a series of occasional papers
issued by PFF, offer replacement models for current regulatory
agencies, departments and laws designed at the height of the Industrial
Era with organizations better suited to meeting the needs of citizens
in the Digital Age.  A private, non-profit, non-partisan idea
center established in 1993, The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation
aims to create a positive vision of the future founded in the
historic principles of the American Idea.  It brings together
a diverse group of thinkers and policy experts and shares their
work with the American people through seminars, conferences, publications
and electronic media of all forms.  Supported by tax deductible
donations from corporations, foundations and individuals, PFF
does not engage in lobbying activities or take positions on legislation.
 The views expressed here are solely those of the author(s) and
do not necessarily represent the views of the Board, Officers
or Staff of The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation.</i>
<P>
<CENTER><I>Permission granted to reproduces as long
as acknowledgment is made.<BR>

<P>
Richard F. O'Donnell, Editor<BR>

The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation<br>
1301 K Street, N.W., Suite 650 West  Washington, DC 20005 
voice: 202/289-8928 fax: 202/289-6079<br>
 <a href="mailto:mail@pff.org">e-mail: mail@pff.org</a>,  <br>internet: 
<a href="http://www.pff.org">http://www.pff.org</a><BR>
</CENTER></font>
<P><br><p><br>
<p><br>
<CENTER><h2>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</h2>
 </B></CENTER>
<P>
During the past 20 years, competition has largely
replaced monopoly as the typical market structure in cargo and
passenger airline service, bus and truck transportation, securities
and financial services markets and many postal services. With
enactment of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the market for
telecommunications seems likely to follow a similar path. 
<P>
In many of these markets, competition has been
facilitated by technological advances that have reduced both the
importance of economies of scale and the cost of information,
creating opportunities for decentralization in areas where monopolies
and bureaucratic decision making once prevailed.  Taken together,
these developments constitute a major competition revolution. 
<P>
Competitive pressures in electricity markets,
already significant because of recent developments freeing up
transmission networks, are now increasing, in part due to the
introduction of more efficient (and environmentally friendly)
generation technologies.  Moreover, a large number of states are
studying or proposing restructuring plans for their electricity
markets, designed to bring the benefits of competition to their
consumers. 
<P>
 One major obstacle has stood in the path of
the competition revolution:  Government regulation.  Regulatory
structures put in place during the Progressive Era ostensibly
to <I>protect </I>consumers are now, ironically, <I>depriving
</I>consumers of the benefits only competition can bring. 
<P>
 Nowhere is this more true today than in the
markets for electric power and natural gas.   A 1935 law, the
Public Utility Holding Company Act<a href="foot.html"><sup>1</sup></a> (PUHCA), is depriving consumers
of hundreds of millions of dollars annually in economic benefits,
slowing the introduction of new technologies and even blocking
the efforts of states to deregulate their own markets. 
<P>
 As this paper demonstrates, repealing PUHCA,
as legislation now before Congress would do, would generate substantial
benefits and impose virtually no costs. The competition revolution
is moving to the market for electricity; government needs to open
the gates and let it in. 
<P>
PUHCA is a depression-era regulatory program
that has outlived its usefulness.  PUHCA's major effect today
is to impede state efforts to bring the benefits of electricity
competition to consumers.  Among the reasons to repeal PUHCA are: 
<UL>
<LI>At the present time, 46 states are at various
stages of implementing competitive restructuring plans of their
electric energy markets.  Six states - California, Illinois, Massachusetts,
New Hampshire, New York and Rhode Island - already have adopted
or are close to adopting restructuring plans that will allow retail
competition in some form.  In many of these cases, the restrictions
imposed by PUHCA will restrict entry and frustrate efforts to
create a competitive electricity market. 
<LI>PUHCA places geographic restrictions on
mergers and limitations on diversification into non-utility lines
of business.  These create artificial barriers to competition
and the efficient allocation of resources.  While these costs
have been reduced by the Telecommunications Act of 1996, which
allows utilities to make better use of their telecommunications-related
assets, too many restrictions still remain. 
<LI>Similarly, PUHCA restricts the &quot;market
for corporate control&quot; by limiting takeovers of electric
and gas utilities.  This reduces the pressure for efficient utilization
of utilities' assets and the resultant savings that would be passed
on to customers. 
<LI>Increased wholesale competition in the
electricity industry and overall competition in gas markets diminish
the need for PUHCA-style regulation.  Competition is not yet sufficient,
however, to make rate regulation unnecessary. 
<LI>In order to trace costs to specific goods
and services and to avoid cross subsidization, many regulated
industries frequently establish separate subsidiaries or affiliates
for certain purposes.   In the energy industry, the holding company
structure is conducive to sound rate regulation.   Current PUHCA
requirements discourage firms from adopting a holding company
structure, and make the regulatory process more difficult for
both regulators and regulatees. 
<LI>Finally, PUHCA is redundant, because the
pervasiveness of other regulatory programs provides ample consumer
protection.  These programs include rate regulation at the state
and federal levels covering consumer prices; antitrust regulation
covering mergers and acquisitions; and, financial disclosure regulation
covering investors. 
</UL>

<P>
PUHCA has out lived whatever usefulness it
may once have had.  Consumers and investors today receive ample
protections through other regulatory and market mechanisms, yet
they are denied the benefits of competition in the energy industry.
<p>
  Repealing PUHCA is an important first step in bringing America's
energy markets into the 21<SUP>st</SUP> century. <be>
<p><hr>
<center>
