</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> V. Puhca versus Efficient Regulation -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<CENTER><h2>V.  PUHCA VS. EFFICIENT REGULATION </h2></CENTER>
<P>
Increases in competition diminish the need
for regulation in general and magnify the importance of PUHCA's
anticompetitive features.  Nevertheless, competition is not yet
sufficient to eliminate the need for maximum rate regulation.
 Paradoxically, PUHCA has effects that are inconsistent with an
efficient regulatory system.  
<P>
<CENTER><B>Increased Competition in Electricity
and Gas </B></CENTER>
<P>
Although competition at the retail level for
electricity has just started to emerge, there has, in recent years,
been a significant increase in wholesale electricity competition.
 In the gas industry, competition has increased at both the wholesale
and retail levels. 
<P>
Wholesale power markets have become increasingly
competitive in recent years, primarily as a result of a series
of legislative and regulatory developments.  Today, large regional
grid networks allow competing suppliers access to wholesale customers
of many sizes and types. 
<P>
The Public Utilities Regulatory Policy Act
of 1978 (PURPA),<a href="foot.html"><sup>37</sup></a>
 created a new class of generators, called qualifying
facilities (QFs) consisting of co-generators and small power producers.
<a href="foot.html"><sup>38</sup></a>
 As a result, non-utility generation increased rapidly in the
1980's, and by 1992 accounted for 10 percent of total U.S. generation.
 
<P>
Wholesale competition also has been facilitated
by the Energy Policy Act of 1992, <a href="foot.html"><sup>39</sup></a>
which permits any person, including
a registered holding company, to acquire an exempt wholesale generator
wherever located, or a foreign utility company (&quot;FUCO&quot;)
without seeking prior approval from the SEC.<a href="foot.html"><sup>40</sup></a> 
The EWGs constitute
an important source of non-utility generation. 
<P>
Today, additional units of generating capacity
are just as likely to be provided by non-utility generators (NUGs,
which include both QFs and EWGs) as by utilities.  During 1990-91,
NUGs added more net capacity than did utilities and forecasts
suggest that the importance of NUG's will increase in the future.
<a href="foot.html"><sup>41</sup></a> 
<P>
The 1992 Energy Policy Act also authorized
FERC to require companies to provide transmission services if
in the public interest.  Pursuant to this provision, the Commission
in April 1996 issued an order that requires all transmission-owning
public  utilities to open their transmission lines to eligible
wholesale customers on a non-discriminatory basis.
<a href="foot.html"><sup>42</sup></a>  Providing
access to the transmission network will increase competitiveness
at the wholesale level and make the state regulators' job easier
and their regulation more effective. 
<P>
The gas market has, in the deregulated environment
of recent years, become much more competitive. In 1978, Congress
passed the Natural Gas Policy Act as part of the National Energy
Plan.  In January 1985, in accordance with Phase 1 of this plan,
wellhead prices for about half the nation's gas supplies were
decontrolled.<a href="foot.html"><sup>43</sup></a>  
Wellhead price controls were eliminated for all
gas supplies by the Natural Gas Wellhead Decontrol Act of 1989. 
<P>
In October 1985, FERC, in Order 436, allowed
pipelines to become open-access transporters of gas bought directly
from producers by all classes of customers.  In November of 1993,
FERC issued Order 636, which basically converted pipelines to
common carrier status and made natural gas procurement, contract
and price negotiations the responsibility of the local distribution
companies. 
<P>
The deregulation of wellhead prices, combined
with greater access to pipeline transportation services, and the
inclusion of many more participants in the natural gas market,
has resulted in a much more competitive market than existed a
decade ago.  The gas industry seems well along in the deregulatory
process and PUHCA simply acts as a drag on the process. 
<P>
<CENTER><B>Regulatory Efficiency </B></CENTER>
<P>
The developments described above mean that
electric utility firms are now faced with wholesale competition
from numerous non-utility generators and other utilities.  Even
in the absence of retail competition, this change in market structure
reduces the need for PUHCA regulation. The price information from
an active wholesale market is a major aid to state regulators
and hence they are able to more easily judge the &quot;reasonableness&quot;
of a local utility's rate requests.  Information generated from
a competitive wholesale market is a high-powered substitute for
the purported informational benefits of PUHCA regulation. 
<P>
PUHCA was intended &quot;to provide a mechanism
to create conditions under which effective federal and state regulation
will be possible.&quot;<a href="foot.html"><sup>44</sup></a> 
 It is, therefore, ironic that the Act
discourages the holding company structure, which is conducive
to efficient regulation. The major purpose of public utility rate
regulation is to insure that rates are reasonable relative to
costs.  The avoidance of unauthorized cross-subsidies is particularly
important for multi-product utilities. 
<P>
Firms with discrete product lines can organize
either through the divisional structure (examples are PacifiCorp
and UtiliCorp) or as holding companies in which the divisions
are separate corporate entities.  The holding company structure
facilitates regulation because it makes it more straightforward
for both the regulator and the regulatee to allocate costs.  Costs
are more easily traceable to the individual products and cross-subsidies
are easier to discern.  It is for this reason that firms in regulated
industries frequently are <I>required</I> to provide certain product
lines through separate subsidiaries or affiliates (for an example,
see section 272 of the Telecommunications Act of 1996, which requires
Bell operating companies to provide certain services through separate
affiliates). 
<P>
The requirements of PUHCA make organizing as
a holding company costly, whatever its other advantages.  If PUHCA
were repealed, it is likely that more firms would organize as
holding companies, thereby improving the regulatory process. 
<br><hr><P>
<center>
<a href="part6.html">Next Section: PUCHA Is Redundant</a><br>
<a href="part4.html">Previous Section: PUCHA Vs. Efficiency</a><br>
<a href="part8.html">References</a><br>
<a href="part9.html">Appendices</a>
</center>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center>
