<DOCHDR>
http://www.cpac.org:80/pff/clean/sect1.html 204.71.237.74 19970109193632 text/html 11405
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Thursday, 09-Jan-97 19:36:13 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 11-Jul-96 19:54:00 GMT
Content-length: 11217
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Introduction</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">I. INTRODUCTION<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><br><p>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Urban air pollution, whether from chimneys,
smokestacks or, later on, from automobiles, is documented as far
back as commentary on urban problems can be found.  First addressed
by common law and later by city and state regulation, the pollution
challenge became the object of federal control in 1970 with passage
of the Clean Air Act.<sup><a href="end.html">1</a></sup> 
Over the years, America achieved significant
progress in reducing emissions, but never enough to meet nationwide
standards.  For instance, in heavily populated regions, pollution
from individual sources was reduced while the number of sources
simultaneously increased.  Indeed, vehicle travel has doubled
since 1970.<sup><a href="end.html">2</a></sup> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Air pollution is a regional phenomenon.  Its
solution requires a decentralized approach that allows flexibility
to address local conditions.  The 1990 amendments to the Clean
Air Act (CAA) recognized that the problem of air pollution cannot
be solved with a national, one-size-fits-all approach - a fundamental
change from the way the nation had previously attempted to achieve
clean air goals.  While the CAA set tighter national standards
for reducing air pollution, it also established even tighter strictures
for more troubled regions.  These regional standards are so tight
that some question their scientific justification.<sup><a href="end.html">3</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The CAA identified 22 U.S. cities, California
and the12 states that form the nation's northeastern quadrant
as regions facing exceptional air pollution problems that require
individualized solutions.   The Act mandated that these regions
achieve significant reductions in the formation of ozone and certain
specified pollutants that come from automobiles, other mobile
sources and industry.  Federal regulators have ordered cities
and states facing the more difficult pollution problems to set
up prescribed systems for inspecting and maintaining automobile
emission controls.  However, pollution from stationary sources
and conventional vehicles can be reduced only so much before the
rising incremental costs make it practically impossible to achieve
significant gains in overall reductions of air pollution.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> Thus in the face of ever-tightening constraints,
communities, states and regions have searched for new ways to
reduce air pollution - in fact, the CAA calls for the development
and deployment of new technologies.  A few established credit
trading programs that allow polluters who cut below mandated levels
to sell credits to others who face higher costs.<sup><a href="end.html">
4</a></sup>  Some pushed
for the use of cleaner-burning fuels.  Others experimented with
ways to induce greater use of mass-transit systems and clean-fuel
vehicles, and some pushed to remove older and dirtier cars from
the highway by allowing industrial polluters to gain credits when
they purchase and destroy the old junkers.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> Added to these programs is a major effort
to develop and introduce alternative fuel (nonpetroleum-based)
vehicles (AFVs).  AFVs have two major benefits:  they are cleaner
and reduce U.S. dependence on petroleum imports.  AFV use is being
encouraged through legislative mandates, presidential executive
orders, the Energy Policy Act of 1992 and the corporate average
fuel economy (CAFE) standards that set the mile-per-gallon fuel
efficiency rate to be achieved by new car fleets .</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Introduction of Alternative
Fuel Vehicles</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> When the CAA was passed, AFVs were far more
than a gleam in some inventor's eye.<sup><a href="end.html">5</a></sup>  Propane-burning vehicles,
which accounted for 10 percent of the vehicles in Holland in 1992,
had been used in the United States for decades.  Methanol- and
ethanol-based fuels, used widely in Brazil, were available for
conventional vehicles throughout most U.S. markets.<sup><a href="end.html">6</a></sup>  Compressed
natural gas (CNG) vehicles dominated a small part of the Italian
market and were a clear contender for expanded use in America.
 And electric vehicles, long seen in airports and on golf courses
in miniature form, were being developed and demonstrated for commuters
in U.S. cities.  Along with alternative fuels, reformulated gasoline
was in the works, and the auto companies were heavily involved
in improving the emission performance of their gasoline engines.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The drafters of the CAA hoped that if somehow
clean automobiles and trucks suddenly emerged on the streets of
nonattainment cities (those not meeting clean air standards),
then part of the emission control battle might be won.   However,
placing a bet on the market prospects for AFVs in 1990 was gambling
on successful development and market acceptance of new technologies.
 The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA's) 1994 summary
of the problem somehow makes all this seem easy:</FONT>
<P><blockquote>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Clean-fueled vehicles are here today and widespread
use in the near future is feasible.  To enable the transition,
technologies must be refined so vehicles can achieve optimum performance
and emissions characteristics.  Consumers must accept the new
vehicles and fuels, and government and industry must cooperate
to ensure their availability.<sup><a href="end.html">7</a></sup> </FONT>

</blockquote><P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> Yet in reality, the challenges facing the
new technologies are enormous.  One need only think of the nation's
deeply embedded driving and fuel-use habits to understand the
magnitude of change required for AFVs to succeed:  consumers purchasing
light vehicles can choose from thousands of models; buyers of
heavy-duty trucks and buses may select from hundreds; and, government
and industry are limited in their options.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"> At any moment in time and in all markets,
new technologies stand before the market's threshold awaiting
their chance.  Entry to the market depends on luck, access to
capital markets, changing relative prices, protection of intellectual
property rights, and the regulatory framework that may in some
cases be protecting existing technologies. Technology-based standards,
commonly found in the environmental arena, can blunt the spur
to introduce new pollution control devices that may stand at the
market's threshold. The role of government in influencing markets
and thus the acceptance of new technology is immense.  For example,
banking statutes and regulations that mandate risk-based capital
requirements can affect credit markets, sometimes introducing
a bias that favors known players and technologies.  In addition,
the patent and common law governing trade secrets can either delay
or hasten the introduction of new production techniques. Antitrust
enforcement limits the exchange of information among competitors
and chills mergers among firms with new and old technologies.
 Various tax and subsidy schemes alter consumer prices and thereby
influence the flow of new technologies.  Finally, government's
role as buyer of goods can either favor or discourage new technologies.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Even if these hurdles are surmounted for at
least part of the AFV market, another difficulty enters the picture.
 Unlike other new products that, for instance, improve communications
or health care, environmental technologies produce a product that
seldom commands a price.  Units of cleaner air are not bought
and sold in conventional markets, and thus it is difficult to
determine the worth of new environmental technologies.  It may
even seem that command-and-control regulation is the only way
to induce air quality improvements.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Can market incentives be called on to help? What is the role played by government in all this?  Are federal
subsidies and taxes the answer?  Do states and cities provide
the appropriate arena of action?  What can we say about national
policy and the prospects for cleaner AFVs?</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This paper addresses these questions and more.
 While recognizing that there are serious questions associated
with the statutes now in place, we nonetheless accept their bright
lines and consider the means that might be chosen to accomplish
the laws' goals.<sup><a href="end.html">8</a></sup>
  Our report first explains the air pollution
problem facing major cities and regions, the statutes attempting
to address the problem, and the related national energy security
problem.  Next the paper explains the institutional framework
that affects the market for all vehicles and especially those
using alternative fuels.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Section III examines the problem confronted
when there is no market for cleaner air and provides details on
federal and state legislation and tax policies that relate to
the problem.  The next section focuses exclusively on AFVs and
examines in some detail six contenders for market entry:  compressed
natural gas, liquefied natural gas, propane, ethanol, methanol
and electric-powered vehicles.  Along the way, key institutional
issues are discussed, and the newly emerging decentralized approach
to the clean air problem is emphasized.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Section V identifies niche markets that are
currently emerging for AFVs.  These include heavy-duty trucks
and other large engine vehicles that do not confront the infrastructure
problem faced by the light vehicle market.  Drawing on the theme
of decentralization, the concluding section provides a policy
proposal for alternative fuel vehicles and other technologies
that might improve air quality.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our proposal calls for the creation of Environmental
Innovation Areas (EIAs) - air quality management regions that
can be freely adopted by any metropolitan area, region or state.
 Bound by national air quality standards that must be maintained,
the EIAs would be given flexibility in devising local approaches
for improving air quality.  Each unique EIA may customize its
use of taxes, subsidies, emission credit markets and other devices
to achieve its clean air targets.  Our plan would also repeal
regulations that limit entry of new technologies.  In addition,
it would require that federal agencies use taxpayer funds to assist
the purchase of mandated AFVs while not favoring or discriminating
against any specific alternative fuel.  The goal of our recommendations
is to encourage experiments in new technology by using the creativity
of the marketplace.</FONT>
<p>
<br>
<a href="sect2.html">Next Section: The Infrastructure Challenge</a><p>
<a href="exec.html">Previous Section: Executive Summary</a><p>
<a href="end.html">End Notes</a>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
