</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">price for electric vehicles exceeding $30,000
and with battery replacement costs running close to half that
amount, the lack of market penetration for electric vehicles is
surely understandable.  As to ethanol, the high demand for corn
has driven up its price, making alcohol production a less attractive
proposition.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In addition to tax incentives for purchasers
of AFVs and alternative fuels, several federal agencies manage
a wide variety of programs that provide grants and subsidies to
states, localities and consumers for the development and implementation
of alternative fuel programs.  For example, EPACT authorizes $10
million per year for financial assistance to state and local AFV
programs. EPACT also allows manufacturers of AFVs to receive credits
that can be applied to the CAFE standard of 27.5 mpg for conventional
motor vehicles.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Through its Urban Consortium Energy Task Force,
the DOE provides funds for energy technology and management programs
in cities and counties.  DOE uses oil overcharge money derived
from prices charged by oil companies during the 1970s' oil embargoes
to fund state energy efficiency programs.  Along with Ford, General
Motors, Chrysler and the Electric Power Research Institute, the
Department of Transportation (DOT) funds the U.S. Advanced Battery
Consortium, which conducts extensive research on electric vehicles
(EVs).  Under the Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency
Act of 1991 (ISTEA), the DOT provides funds for state transportation
programs and projects that improve air quality.  ISTEA authorizes
the use of federal funds for the conversion and purchase of centrally-fueled
AFVs and for on-site fueling facilities for publicly-owned fleets.
The National Air and Space Administration and DOT also provide
support for AFV research from their research budgets.
<sup><a href="end.html">62</a></sup><BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">State Alternative Fuel Regulations,
Laws and Incentives</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Interest in AFVs appears to be universal among
states.  As of November 1994, all fifty states and the District
of Columbia had enacted statutes, written regulations or issued
executive orders that in some way facilitate the use of alternative
fuels in motor vehicles.  These measures range from very minor
and relatively passive measures to complicated and detailed mandates,
tax credits, tax deductions, grants and other measures supporting
the acquisition of AFVs and stimulation of AFV technologies.
<sup><a href="end.html">63</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">California illustrates the range of these actions.
 The state has a comprehensive set of subsidies and mandates contained
in at least 15 statutes related to the use of vehicles that produce
lower emissions than conventional gasoline powered vehicles. 
One such statute requires the state to purchase 25 percent AFVs
as it replaces the state fleet.  Another statute allows a 55 percent
tax credit, up to $1,000 per passenger vehicle and up to $3,500
for heavier vehicles, for those who purchase low emission vehicles
or retrofit conventional vehicles.  California also sets an excise
tax on fuels with 85 percent ethanol or methanol that is one-half
the rate charged on gasoline.  For operators of flexible-fuel
vehicles in the air quality district, the Sacramento Metropolitan
Air Quality Management District annually offers $500 of &quot;free&quot;
85 percent methanol fuels.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">At the other extreme, Indiana provides no state
funds or mandates for AFVs, but the state government offers assistance
to private firms and localities in attracting federal grants for
AFV activities.  Like Indiana, Kentucky has no incentives or mandates,
but has several small demonstration projects and has received
DOE funding for four retail CNG refueling stations.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As noted in Table 1, federal motor fuel excise
taxes favor some alternative fuels over gasoline and diesel fuel.
 State taxes paint an entirely different picture.  Table 3 shows
state tax rates for gasoline, diesel and four alternative fuels.
 A number of states listed in the table provide special fuel tax
treatment for AFVs with decals purchased from the state.  The
annual decal fees range from $30 for light vehicles to $4,060
for heavy-duty trucks and buses depending on the weight and annual
mileage of the covered vehicle.  For example, Louisiana requires
a $150/year decal, which exempts operators of propane and natural
gas vehicles from fuel taxes.  Alabama requires an AFV decal for
a fee that ranges from $75 to $175 depending on vehicle weight.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">With some rather modest exceptions, state taxes
per gallon of fuel differ very little across the six fuels listed
in the table. Since federal taxes favor alternative fuels over
gasoline and diesel, and since most states tax fuels are approximately
the same by volume, the sum of state and federal excise taxes
would appear to provide implicit subsidies for alternative fuels.
Table 4 gives these sums.  However, fuel energy content, not volume,
is the more relevant unit of measurement. Table 5 shows the sum
of state and federal excise taxes based on the BTU equivalent
of one gallon of gasoline. Viewed in BTU terms, CNG receives a
relatively favorable treatment. Ethanol is treated favorably,
but the tax savings on ethanol consumption is considerably lower
than for CNG.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Table 3</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">STATE FUEL TAXES* </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Arial">(cents
per gallon)<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=103><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">State</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=84><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Gasoline</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=81><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Diesel</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=87><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Methanol</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=78><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Ethanol</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=78><CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">CNG</FONT></B></CENTER>
