</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=103><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Wisconsin</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=89><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">41.5</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=80><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">40.5</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=90><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">69.6</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">37.4</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">28.7</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">56.3</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=103><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Wyoming</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH=89><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">27.4</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=80><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">28.5</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=90><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">41.2</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">22.8</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">5.6</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">24.9</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=103><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">Mean</FONT></TD><TD WIDTH=89><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">37.76</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=80><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">37.2</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=90><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">56.11</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">32.34</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">19.11*</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">47.56*</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=1 FACE="Arial">*These calculations exclude decal and
fee states. Source: Computed from Tables 1 and 2 above.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">On the other hand, current state tax laws substantially
penalize the use of methanol.  Only six states (Alaska, Arkansas,
Colorado, New Jersey, Oklahoma and Vermont) tax methanol at a
lower rate than gasoline and diesel fuel.  All other states and
the District of Columbia tax methanol at a higher rate.  In most
states there is also an excise tax penalty for using propane.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The combined effect of state and federal fuel
taxes, considered in the light of emission characteristics, form
an interesting picture.  CNG and LPG are cleaner burning than
ethanol- and methanol-blends of gasoline.  The tax structure favors
CNG and ethanol and penalizes methanol and LPG.  However, the
effects of combined taxes are not as unfavorable on air quality
grounds as the federal tax system considered in isolation suggests.
 The federal tax system appears to reflect a massive political
struggle among the various fuel providers.  Apparently, ethanol
achieved a major victory; LPG did not do so well.  This outcome
tells us that the political process may not be well suited to
establish emission-based fuel taxes.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">State taxes suggest the reverse of federal
programs.  Certainly the data reveals the influence of special
interests.  For instance, states that are specialized in the production
of corn favor ethanol; those that produce natural gas favor gas-based
fuels.  But overall, the state schemes come much closer to setting
taxes based on emissions than does the federal scheme.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The outcome suggests that competition matters.
 States compete for population, economic development and environmental
protection.  The national government does not face the same competition.
 The record suggests strongly that states should focus on emission-based
fuel taxes that provide incentives for all fuel producers to achieve
higher environmental standards.  The national government should
address primarily the highway user-fee component of the fuel tax,
while perhaps paying some attention to emission-based taxes that
address national environmental concerns.<BR>
</FONT>
<p><br>
