<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>IV.AFV Emission and Cost Characteristics </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>
<CENTER>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">IV. AFV EMISSION AND COST CHARACTERISTICS</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>

<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Conventional wisdom and anecdotal evidence
tell us that the first automobiles on the dusty roads of America
encountered many naysayers.  Early drivers were greeted by catcalls
and &quot;Get a horse!&quot;  Availability of fuel was a problem,
and no one could imagine how the new technology might affect the
environment.  Indeed, few people cared.  Today, what can we say
about AFVs, their emission characteristics and costs?  Which of
the AFVs is in the best position to enter the market?
<sup><a href="end.html">64</a></sup>   </FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Compressed Natural Gas</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">It is estimated that in 1990 there were 500,000
CNG powered vehicles worldwide.  In the United States today, some
84,000 CNG vehicles ply the roads, 49 percent of which are pickups
(most of them bi-fuel vehicles).<sup><a href="end.html">65</a></sup>
  Ford offers its Crown Victoria,
Econoline van and F150/250 pickups for the CNG market.  Chrysler
sells its CNG Voyagers, Caravans, Dakota and Ram pickups, while
General Motors is reentering the market with sedans.  Meanwhile
Chrysler, Ford, Cummins, Mack Truck, Caterpillar, and Detroit
Diesel are developing natural gas engines for vehicle use. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Natural gas is a fossil fuel extracted either
from natural gas wells or from wells that produce both crude oil
and natural gas.  Because of its very low energy density, natural
gas needs to be used as compressed gas (CNG) or liquefied and
stored cryogenically (LNG).  Either method requires heavier, more
expensive storage systems than those found in conventional vehicles.
CNG vehicles can be bi-fuel (natural gas and either diesel or
gasoline) or dedicated to natural gas, which optimizes performance.
 When properly tuned, a single-fuel natural gas vehicle has superior
power and efficiency to a gasoline engine.  An engine dedicated
to natural gas can have a higher compression ratio, increasing
thermal efficiency 10-20 percent, which compensates for the heavier
tanks required for containing the compressed fuel.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are two refueling options for CNG vehicles:
 (1) Fast-fill at a compressor-equipped refueling station or (2)
at home or work, which takes several hours for a typical light
vehicle.  The fast-fill method requires a greater infrastructure
investment, as much as $500,000 for an average volume station.
<sup><a href="end.html">66</a></sup>
 As for home refueling, much of the infrastructure is in place,
because most homes are connected to a natural gas utility system.
 With a small compressor unit, which costs approximately $5,000,
CNG vehicles could be filled at home using overnight filling.
Compared to gasoline, dedicated CNG engines have longer engine
lives and lower maintenance costs due to the cleaner burn of CNG.
<sup><a href="end.html">67</a></sup>
 As to safety and health concerns, natural gas is less subject
to self-ignition than gasoline, and the release of natural gas,
which is nontoxic, does not cause a serious health hazard.
<sup><a href="end.html">68</a></sup>  The
per-mile injury rate for CNG vehicles is 37 percent lower than
for gasoline fleet vehicles and 34 percent lower than all gasoline
vehicles.<sup><a href="end.html">69</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">CNG is being used in fleets across the country.
 A central refueling point makes fleet usage attractive.  For
example, the Peachtree City, Georgia, police force recently converted
its twelve patrol cars to CNG.  Schools in Tulsa, Oklahoma (120
buses), and Aurora, Colorado (53 buses), are using CNG buses.
 The cities of Milton, Florida (25 police cars, sedans and garbage
trucks), and West Vancouver, British Columbia (40 police, utility,
and administrative vehicles), are successfully  using CNG vehicles.
<sup><a href="end.html">70</a></sup>
 The American Gas Association estimates that more than 25 U.S.
school districts have converted five or more buses to CNG use.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Not surprisingly, natural gas companies are
at the forefront in using natural gas vehicles.  An American Gas
Association survey in 1991 revealed that 8,827 natural gas vehicles
are part of the fleets of 82 U.S. utility companies.
<sup><a href="end.html">71</a></sup>  In order
to reduce air pollution, water clouding and fuel bills, Disneyland
converted much of their transportation system (60 boats and rafts,
one submarine, four Main Street vehicles, and 16 service vehicles)
to CNG. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">United Parcel Service implemented a CNG program
for its delivery vehicles in New York City, the District of Columbia,
Dallas, Los Angeles, Tulsa and Oklahoma City.  The firm reports
a maintenance cost drop of $1.00 per vehicle per day, a 30 percent
reduction in fuel costs and reductions in pollution (18 percent
less CO, 86 percent less nonmethane hydrocarbons, and 22 percent
less NOx).<sup><a href="end.html">72</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The U.S. Postal Service (USPS), which now has
thousands of CNG vehicles, tested seven types of alternative fuels
in their vehicles and found that CNG was the only fuel tested
that is economical, safe and viable.<sup><a href="end.html">73</a></sup>
  They incurred costs of converting
to CNG of $1,500-$2,500 per vehicle and increased vehicle weight
by 200 pounds.  USPS concluded that electric vehicles had high
maintenance, costs and limited range.  Propane (LPG) vehicles
tested were deemed unsafe and did not reduce reliance on imported
oil.  Liquefied natural gas (LNG) tanks required too much space.
 Methanol suffered from low fuel economy and corrosive effects
on engines.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Research on fuels for AFVs focuses primarily
on light vehicles and is generally incomplete.  Comparisons of
studies are difficult to make, since the tests reported are often
for different vehicles using different test techniques.  For these
reasons, we report a series of findings, which turn out to be
rather wide-ranging.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">On the basis of these studies, CNG turns out
to be a rather clean fuel.  Evaporative emissions from CNG are
zero since refueling and storage requires a sealed system.  Because
of more complete combustion, carbon monoxide (CO) and non-methane
hydrocarbon emissions are substantially lower than for conventional
gasoline.  NOx emissions may be higher, but in dedicated engines
special combustion chambers can reduce NOx emissions.  When substituting
natural gas for diesel, particulates cease to be a problem, but
NOx surfaces again.  In one comprehensive review, the author reports
a consensus that natural gas has a 20 percent advantage over gasoline
when it comes to greenhouse emissions (GHG), and is neutral in
GHG relative to diesel.<sup><a href="end.html">74</a></sup> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Department of Energy has not yet completed
its final assessment of emissions for CNG vehicles.  However,
one DOE report concludes that using CNG lowers CO emissions by
six to 99 percent, a range too wide to be very instructive.  NOx
emissions range from 40 percent higher to 85 percent lower, and
hydrocarbon (HC) emmisions range from 697 percent higher to 44
percent lower for passenger cars.  However, much of the increased
HC is methane, which does not contribute to ozone.  In short,
the overall effect of CNG use would be ozone reducing.
<sup><a href="end.html">75</a></sup> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In a California Council for Environmental and
Economic Balance study of CNG, CO emissions were 50 to 90 percent
lower than for gasoline vehicles, HC emissions were 50 to 80 percent
lower, and particulates were nearly eliminated.  NOx emissions,
which are subject to temperature and the presence of oxygen, were
shown to be as much as 80 percent higher.<sup><a href="end.html">76</a></sup>  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A 1990 EPA report estimates that CNG vehicles
will reduce volatile organic chemicals (VOCs), an ozone precursor,
by 36 to 47 percent in bi-fuel vehicles and 80 to 90 percent in
engines dedicated to natural gas.<sup><a href="end.html">77</a></sup>
  It is important to note the
EPA's findings, given the agency's lead role in regulating mobile
source emissions.  An American Petroleum Institute report agrees
that dedicated engines reduce VOCs 80 to 93 percent, but estimates
the bi-fuel systems will generate 75 to 86 percent less VOCs.
<sup><a href="end.html">78</a></sup>
 A study by the Gas Research Institute<sup><a href="end.html">79</a></sup>
 estimates 83 percent less
reactive organic gases, another measure of ozone precursors, and
another exhaustive report estimates that CNG use has 60 percent
lower ozone-forming potential than do gasoline vehicles.
<sup><a href="end.html">80</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A 1995 report prepared for the Natural Gas
Coalition compared emissions for nine different light vehicles
and provided some data for heavy-duty trucks and locomotives.
 Net smog-forming emissions for CNG vehicles, which accounts for
volume as well as reactivity of emissions gases, were 87 percent
less than those from gasoline engine vehicles.  Emissions of NOx
from heavy-duty vehicle engines were at levels that could not
be achieved by diesel engines.<sup><a href="end.html">81</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As with emission estimates, the estimated cost
of moving to CNG vehicles varies widely from study to study. 
A 1994 survey of AFV studies reports the overall costs of CNG
range from 74 percent to 170 percent of the cost of a gasoline-fueled
light vehicle.<sup><a href="end.html">82</a></sup>
  The DOE estimates that light vehicle conversion
costs range from $2,700 to $5,000.<sup><a href="end.html">83</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In a more comprehensive study, the American
Petroleum Institute examined the incremental costs, including
private and social costs, of the adoption of CNG for three cases.
<sup><a href="end.html">84</a></sup>
 The first is a private CNG vehicle program with a public refueling
program.  The second is for centrally fueled fleets in nine cities.
 The third case involves the use of new CNG transit buses in metropolitan
areas having a population greater than one million people.  The
costs of emissions reductions were calculated at avoided costs
(the cost effectiveness of achieving the same reductions through
other means).</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In all three cases, the net private benefit
of CNG vehicles is negative, and in all three cases, the net social
benefit may be positive (which accounts for air quality improvements
as well as private costs and benefits).<sup><a href="end.html">85</a></sup>
  For example, CNG use
in Los Angeles light vehicles would have a private cost ranging
from $0.01 to $0.36 per gallon equivalent, but would yield overall
social benefits as large as $0.55 or overall costs of $0.01 per
gallon.  For transit buses, the net private costs range from $0.04
to $0.50 per gallon equivalent, but the social benefit ranged
from a high of $0.35 per gallon to a loss of $.027 per gallon.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Liquefied Natural Gas</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Liquefied natural gas (LNG) is natural gas
stored in liquid form at refrigerated temperature levels; it therefore
shares many of the features of CNG.  The liquid form offers an
advantage over the compressed form.  The fuel is stored at low
pressures (10 to 25 psi), which yields rapid refueling capability
and the use of smaller storage tanks.  However, with the added
bulk of insulation, LNG tanks are about twice as large as gasoline
tanks for an equivalent amount of energy.</FONT><P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A major disadvantage of LNG is that the refrigeration
can consume 25 percent of the energy of the natural gas being
liquefied.  This adds roughly $0.20 per gallon equivalent to the
cost of the natural gas.  There is also a potential frostbite
problem associated with the handling of LNG, but all other technological
assessments are essentially the same between LNG and CNG.  Emissions
characteristics, of course, are the same as CNG use.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">LNG is in use in a substantial number of heavy-duty
truck and bus demonstration fleets, but few light-duty AFVs are
currently operating on LNG.  There is a potential use of LNG as
a fuel for heavy-duty vehicles,<sup><a href="end.html">86</a></sup>
 particularly if the federal taxes
on LNG and CNG are equalized.<sup><a href="end.html">87</a></sup>
  Since LNG is a liquid fuel, it
is taxed at about a 12 cents per gallon higher rate than CNG.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Even with the tax disadvantages, LNG has penetrated
some major markets. The Houston (Texas) Metro has announced its
commitment to convert 300 of its buses to LNG use, and Roadway
Express, operator of 3,500 long-haul moving trucks and 5,800 local
moving vans, is considering using LNG fuel in its trucks.
<sup><a href="end.html">88</a></sup>  However,
the federal tax penalty on LNG, as compared to other alternative
fuels, makes the conversion far less attractive.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Liquefied Petroleum Gas</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) can be formed
from a mixture of gases including propane, butane and ethane.
 In the United States, LPG is primarily composed of propane, and
the terms LPG and propane are often used interchangeably.
<sup><a href="end.html">89</a></sup>  LPG
has been used as a commercial fuel for more than 60 years.  Currently,
more than 300,000 vehicles in the United States and four million
vehicles worldwide operate on LPG, although only a small percentage
(2.8 percent) of the U.S. count is used for transportation.
<sup><a href="end.html">90</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">LPG is liquefied by compressing the gas to
a pressure of more than 100 psi to reduce its volume for transportation
and storage.  This requires as much as 45 percent more tank space
than gasoline for an equivalent operating range.
<sup><a href="end.html">91</a></sup>  LPG tanks are
heavier than gasoline counterparts, but the fuel is lighter, which
yields a minimal net weight increase.
<sup><a href="end.html">92</a></sup>  Engine operating and combustion
characteristics yield cleaner starts, which increase engine life
by 50 percent or more.<sup><a href="end.html">93</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Engines can be dedicated to LPG or can be bi-fuel
(with either diesel or gasoline).  Using a dual-fuel system reduces
the efficiency of using propane and requires the complication
of having two simultaneous fuel systems.  Diesel engines can also
be converted to LPG usage, reducing the emission of particulates.
 At present, engine builders are working on dedicated LPG engines
for heavy duty use.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In the United States, most LPG is produced
from stripping wet gases from natural gas, and the remainder is
a by-product of oil refining.  LPG represents three percent of
natural gas and oil reserves.<sup><a href="end.html">94</a></sup>
  It is unclear if the availability
of LPG will be sufficient for widespread use as an alternative
fuel. For instance, a California Energy Commission report predicts
supply shortages, particularly in the winter months when propane
is used as a heating fuel.<sup><a href="end.html">95</a></sup>
  However, other studies show that supply
is not a constraint on LPG use in America.  U.S. refiners are
expected to increase their production of LPG due to changes in
refining processes, and the availability of imported LPG is also
projected to increase (which, of course, works against EPACT's
policy of reducing the importation of fuels).</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Substituting LPG for gasoline reduces CO emissions
by as much as 23 percent, due to the fuel's lower carbon-to-hydrogen
ratio and higher thermal efficiency.  CO, HC, and NOx emissions
depend on the air-fuel ratio.  CO falls as the ratio increases,
HC falls, then increases as the ratio increases, and NOx increases,
then drops as the ratio increases.  Therefore, there is an HC/NOx
tradeoff at different air-fuel ratios.<sup><a href="end.html">96</a></sup>
  CO reductions are the
largest relative to gasoline.  EPA reports an 80 percent reduction,
making LPG attractive for use in confined spaces such as warehouses.
<sup><a href="end.html">97</a></sup>
 EPA also reports nonmethane hydrocarbon reductions for current
LPG vehicles of 41 percent.  Chang estimates a 35 percent reduction
in ozone-forming potential (OFP),<sup><a href="end.html">98</a></sup>
 but Cleanfleet reports a 68
to 71 percent OFP reduction.  Due to a relatively less expensive
storage system, LPG conversions generally cost less than CNG conversions.
 Estimates usually range from $700 to $1500.  Fuel prices are
in the same range as CNG prices.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Methanol</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Methanol is an alcohol-based fuel.  While natural
gas is currently the least expensive and widely used raw material
for methanol production, the fuel also can be made from coal or
biomass.<sup><a href="end.html">99</a></sup>
  Methanol can be used in neat form (M100 or 100 percent
methanol), but is currently only used as a gasoline blend (M85,
or 85 percent methanol).  The fuel has a high octane rating, and
its efficiency increases with an increased compression ratio and
with an increased leaning of the air/fuel mixture, which increases
engine efficiency by approximately 10 percent relative to gasoline.
 Methanol fueled engines can produce more horsepower than their
gasoline counterparts, but the gains are offset by the necessary
heavier fuel tank.<sup><a href="end.html">100</a></sup>
  Because of its power-to-volume traits, a methanol
AFV must have an 80 percent larger tank than a gasoline vehicle
for an equivalent driving range.  Pure methanol presents a cold-start
problem that is resolved with 85 percent blends with gasoline.
 The blend with gasoline obviously reduces some of the air quality
advantages.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Methanol is highly corrosive, but corrosion
inhibitors in the fuel, particular alloys and polymers in engines,
and certain lubricants can help to overcome this problem.  The
fuel conducts electricity, is volatile, burns with an invisible
flame and has wide-ranging flammability limits.  Methanol is highly
toxic, but odorless and tasteless, which increases exposure risks.
 Other problems include accelerated cylinder wear, fuel system
durability for unaltered engine parts (due to its corrosiveness),
and the explosivity of vapor in fuel tanks at ambient temperatures.
 Adding gasoline to pure methanol to form M85 mitigates the invisible
flame and vapor explosivity problems.  Blends allow the fuel to
be identified by odor or taste, a valuable property for a toxic
substance.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As a practical matter, domestically produced
methanol is not a current contender for a major role the U.S.
AFV fleet market.  The plant capacity does not exist, and while
U.S. production facilities could be expanded at exceptionally
high costs, substantial and immediate increases in demand would
likely be satisfied from overseas, which provides little in the
way of energy security benefits.<sup><a href="end.html">101</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">There are no standardized test procedures for
methanol, thus it is difficult to characterize the test data.
Some research indicate methanol use will reduce CO and HC, but
NOx emissions could increase or decrease.  Depending on gasoline
blends, VOCs could decrease by as much as 80 percent and ozone
forming potential by 30 percent.  However, an American Petroleum
Institute study shows reductions in VOCs to range from zero to
75 percent and ozone reductions to average 13 percent.
<sup><a href="end.html">102</a></sup>  The findings
for NOx indicates that methanol vehicles could not meet California
standards.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In 1994, Chrysler offered three light vehicles
equipped for 85 percent methanol; Ford produced one.
<sup><a href="end.html">103</a></sup>  In 1995,
Chrysler reduced its offering to one vehicle while Ford continued
to make its single offering.  The corrosive nature of the fuel
creates substantial hurdles for engine manufacture and modification.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Ethanol</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Ethanol is the most widely used alternative
fuel in the world.  Brazil, with more than four million vehicles
using ethanol, has a highly subsidized program to produce ethanol
from sugarcane.<sup><a href="end.html">104</a></sup>
  All standard gasoline-fueled vehicles can burn
ethanol/gasoline blends with little, if any, difficulty.  In 1988,
880 million gallons of ethanol were produced in the United States,
blended with gasoline and used as a motor fuel, accounting for
almost one percent of the motor fuel market.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In the United States, ethanol is produced from
corn and thus is dependent on the world price of grain.  Like
methanol, ethanol is an alcohol fuel that can be used as 100 percent
ethanol or as a blend with gasoline (10 percent ethanol/90percent
gasoline blend is known as gasohol).  Ethanol's corrosion properties
lie between those of gasoline and methanol.  Most vehicles, however,
can use gasohol without problems.  Ethanol burns with a luminous
flame, unlike methanol, making it easier to detect fires.  It
is less flammable than methanol, but can be explosive in tank
vapor space.  It has no known carcinogenic compounds, but ingestion
can nevertheless cause severe problems.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Ethanol blends do not provide significant improvements
in smog-forming emissions. An American Petroleum Institute study
concludes that total VOC emissions are 20 percent higher for vehicles
using ethanol blended fuel.<sup><a href="end.html">105</a></sup>
   EPA estimates an impact of 15 percent
higher VOCs in 1990 and 20 percent higher in 2000.
<sup><a href="end.html">106</a></sup>  In addition,
NOx emissions tend to be higher with gasohol than gasoline. When
ethanol is substituted for diesel, the main benefit is reductions
in particulates.  HC and CO standards can be met, but NOx emissions
may be a problem.   In 1995, efforts by EPA to require the use
of ethanol in reformulated gasoline were stopped by the U.S. Court
of Appeals (D.C.).<sup><a href="end.html">107</a></sup>
  The court chastised EPA for pushing ethanol
in a program designed to produce cleaner air when EPA itself had
admitted there were no environmental benefits and that ethanol
&quot;might make air quality worse.&quot;<sup><a href="end.html">108</a>
</sup> </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Currently ethanol costs substantially more
to produce than gasoline.  Production costs range from $1.10-$1.65
per gallon, making wholesale costs almost double that of gasoline.
 Since a gallon of ethanol has two-thirds the energy of a gallon
of gasoline, ethanol, which wholesales for, say, $1.20 per gallon,
equates to a gasoline cost of $1.80 per gallon. Since ethanol
blends require no changes to the vehicle and distribution poses
no problems, the higher price of the fuel is the only relevant
cost.  Of course, a substantial increase in demand for ethanol
could raise other issues.  For example, reliance on gasoline for
ethanol blends reduces the national security benefits of this
alternative fuel and the associated increase in demand for corn
could, in turn, increase food prices.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Electric vehicles </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Popular in the late 1800s, electric vehicles
(EVs) have been in use for more than a century.  Of the 4,200
vehicles sold in 1900, 38 percent were electric vehicles, 22 percent
were gasoline fueled and 40 percent were steam powered.
<sup><a href="end.html">109</a></sup>  The invention
of the electric starter in 1911 eliminated the major inconvenience
of gasoline-fueled vehicles, thus eliminating the demand for EVs.
 Since then there have been three surges in interest in EVs. 
The first, in the 1960s, was due primarily to air quality concerns.
 The second, in the 1970s, was a result of the concerns over the
U.S. dependence on imported oil.  The third began in the mid-1980s
and continues to the present.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Relying on ubiquitous standard electricity,
EVs have no refueling problems.  Since there is no energy combustion
on board, there are no tailpipe and no vehicle emissions.  But
storage of electricity in vehicle batteries raises a major constraint.
 EVs in the 1960s used tubular lead-acid batteries.  Many different
technologies have been tried since then, but potential problems
including high costs, questionable durability and the recycling
of toxic components remain.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Aside from their high purchase price, which
currently approaches $30,000, EVs are not particularly attractive
to motorists due to long recharging times, lack of heating and
air conditioning, reduced range, and limited speed and acceleration
compared to gasoline vehicles.  Existing battery technology limits
the driving range to about 100 miles between charges, and replacing
batteries that have a two-year life runs as much as $10,000.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As a result of intense R&amp;D efforts, the
performance for batteries increased 30 percent in the past decade.
 They are now expected to last 30,000 miles with deep dis-charge
cycles and longer with light use and frequent charging.  Advanced
maintenance-free designs are expected to last up to 60,000 miles.
<sup><a href="end.html">110</a></sup>
 Due to lengthy charging periods, EVs are often charged at night,
which dovetails in nicely with the excess generating capacity
of electrical utilities. But EVs are substantially heavier than
their gasoline or diesel counterparts due to the battery weight,
adding to their energy use per mile.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EV marketing efforts received a potential reversal
when the Ozone Transport Commission moved toward the new National
Low Emission Vehicle as the flagship of its ozone control efforts.
 Despite that, General Motors announced that it will offer an
EV produced by its Saturn Division in the fall of 1996.
<sup><a href="end.html">111</a></sup>  This
EV, to be marketed in Los Angeles, San Diego, Phoenix and Tucson,
will have a 70-mile range and sell in the mid-$30,000 price range.
 Chrysler is offering a $100,000 minivan conversion.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The elimination of tail-pipe emissions is the
major benefit of EVs.  If the electricity is generated from nonpolluting
sources (nuclear, wind, water, solar), then there may be clear
environmental benefits. But, if power generation comes from fossil-fuel
powerplants, then pollution concentration may actually increase.
 Thus while EVs have an extreme advantage in point-of-use emissions,
they do not necessarily reduce global emissions.  For this reason,
EVs may address local nonattainment problems at the expense of
regional air quality.  For instance, a DOE paper cites one study
that estimates the changes resulting from substituting EVs for
conventional vehicles in Southern California's South Coast Air
Basin to be HC reduction of 98.9 percent; CO, by 98.7 percent;
and, NOx, by 60.9 percent.  SOx increased by 495.8 percent, and
particulates, by 570.5 percent.<sup><a href="end.html">112</a></sup>  The increases were due to emissions
from coal-burning power plants.  If the electricity had been nuclear
generated (as in the case of Chicago), then there would be no
SOx and particulates emission increases.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EVs suffer from severe cost penalties arising
from lower power and limited range.  Weight limitations impose
another restriction.  EVs are small.  An American Petroleum Institute
study by Henderson and Rusin concludes that these penalties range
from $6,700 to $7,700 per vehicle.<sup><a href="end.html">113</a>
</sup>  The study concluded that EV
life-cycle costs are from $2,000 to $5,000 more than a conventional
vehicle, which gives a total incremental cost of from $8,700 to
$12,700.  Mass production of EVs would likely bring substantial
reductions in vehicle prices.  But the prospects for their widespread
use are still rather dim.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Summary and Comparisons</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Upon completing our review of the various emission
studies described here, we returned to a 1990 General Accounting
Office (GAO) report that summarized similar findings.
<sup><a href="end.html">114</a></sup>  The GAO
summary closely parallels our findings.  Focusing on four of the
alternative fuels, the report states that CNG reduces hydrocarbons
by an estimated 40 to 90 percent and may reduce CO emissions by
50 to 90 percent.  According to the report, LPG produces 50 percent
fewer hydrocarbon emissions and may reduce CO by 25 to 80 percent.
Methanol was found to reduce ozone-forming hydrocarbons by as
much as 40 percent when blended in an 85 percent mix with gasoline.
 Ethanol had similar characteristics.  The GAO summary and our
review suggest strongly that CNG is the cleanest of the gas-based
and alcohol fuels, followed by LPG, methanol and ethanol.  Of
course electricity is the cleanest of all, if the generating source
is nonpolluting.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our assessment of AFV characteristics and costs
indicates that LPG and CNG vehicles have emerged as competitive
technologies in niche markets.  Many fleet owners are already
turning to CNG as a fuel source in order to cut transportation
costs and provide environmental benefits.  LPG is a weak second-place
contender, and its reliance on petroleum feedstocks places the
fuel at a disadvantage when assessed in terms of energy security.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Of the alcohol fuels, ethanol is clearly a
strong contender.  Its market penetration is not hampered by the
availability of refueling stations, but its supply depends on
the relative price of corn. Ethanol received the most favorable
tax and government incentive support, but even with heavy subsidies
its production has faltered in recent years.  Since ethanol is
blended with gasoline, the fuel does not provide the emission
reductions of LPG and CNG.  Methanol's corrosion and safety problems
puts it in last place in the gas and alcohol technology struggle.
 Relative to the other AFVs, electric vehicles are clearly in
an early stage of technological development.  EVs are being produced,
and significant and productive R&amp;D is underway.  With breakthroughs
in battery technologies, EVs could become a contender in the highly
specialized small commuter car market.  At present, however, we
do not see EVs as a major force in the light vehicle market.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our review of AFV emission and cost characteristics
provides a basis for drawing some tentative conclusions regarding
emission reduction costs.  We emphasize the word &quot;tentative.&quot;
 As noted before, there is no single set of consistent emission
and cost studies for all AFVs.  The first approach we took illustrates
the wide variation in costs.  Here, we estimated a set of emission
reduction costs for CNG-AFVs and EVs using the Gas Research Institute
emission data on reactive organic gases and cost estimates provided
by Deborah Gordon that reflect fuel and retrofit costs alone.
<sup><a href="end.html">115</a></sup>
 These calculations show the cost of reducing one ton of ozone
precursors to be $16,194 for CNG and $91,679 to $155,233 for EVs.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In the interest of providing a more comprehensive
and practical basis for estimating the cost of reducing a ton
of smog-forming emissions, we took EPA data on VOCs emissions,
ranges of purchase premium values and EPA's mid-point estimate
for fuel costs for light vehicles fueled with CNG, LPG, ethanol
and methanol.  We recognize that smog production requires interaction
of NOx with VOCs but were unable to obtain comprehensive data
that showed interaction for AFVs.  We made our calculations without
assigning any dollar value to improved environmental quality.
 In brief, our calculations simply reflected the costs paid by
consumers who might purchase AFVs.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Our calculations relied on a number of key
items of EPA data.  These were supplemented with several critical
assumptions.  The fuel prices used in the calculations were drawn
from the EPA database for 1990. We assumed the typical vehicle
fleet has a 10-year life, so we used an undiscounted one-tenth
share of the price premium as the annual fixed charge for each
AFV.  For the analysis, we assumed the vehicles achieve an average
of 20 mpg and are driven 20,000 miles annually.  On this basis,
an average AFV would use the equivalent of 1,000 gallons of gasoline
annually.  The range of annual fuel charges and purchase price
premiums for each vehicle formed our annual incremental cost.
<sup><a href="end.html">116</a></sup>
 For example, EPA's upper estimate for the premium for CNG light
vehicles is $3,250.  Our calculations showed the annual incremental
cost for CNG including fuel costs is $265 per vehicle.  That for
blended ethanol is $960, while blended methanol vehicles carry
an annual incremental cost of $110.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We then considered a hypothetical fleet of
17,231,516 passenger cars, which happens to be size of the 1991
California fleet.  If the hypothetical fleet used conventional
gasoline, then, using EPA's baseline of 1.75 g/mile of VOCs, approximately
665,000 tons of VOCs would be emitted in one year.  If the entire
fleet were converted to CNG, there would be roughly 615,000 fewer
tons.  The annual incremental cost per ton would be $7,400.  Converting
the entire fleet to 85 percent ethanol would likely increase VOCs
emissions.  But methanol blends would reduce VOCs by approximately
435,000 tons annually at a cost of $4,300 per ton.  Unfortunately,
EPA provided no data for VOCs on LPG vehicles.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Finally, to place AFVs in perspective with
vehicles using reformulated gasoline (RFG), we made similar calculations
for that fuel, drawing on other reports for data and assuming
the entire fleet is converted to RFG vehicles.<sup><a href="end.html">117</a>
</sup>  That conversion
would remove approximately 133,000 tons of VOCs at a cost per
ton of $2,600.  Table 6 summarizes our findings.  Recall, the
1991 baseline fleet using conventional gasoline emitted 665,000
tons of VOC.  A move to 100 percent RFG vehicles would reduce
133,000 tons at the lowest price per ton of $2,600.  However,
more than 500,000 tons would remain.  Conversion to methanol blends
would reduce 435,000 tons at a price per ton of $4,300.  More
than 200,000 tons would remain.  CNG vehicles would practically
eliminate all the VOCs at a price per ton of $7,400.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Table 6</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Comparison of Costs Per Ton of VOCs
Reduced<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD WIDTH=213></TD><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Tons Reduced</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Cost per Ton</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">CNG</FONT></B></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">615,000</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><FONT FACE="Arial">$7,400</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=213><CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">E85</FONT></B></CENTER>
