<html><head>
<title>Environmental Innovation Areas</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717"
Vlink="545454" ALINK="#FF0000"><ul><blockquote>
 <a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif"
 align="right" border="0"></a>

<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">VI. ENVIRONMENTAL INNOVATION AREAS:
 A REGIONAL APPROACH TO ACHIEVING NATIONAL GOALS<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Think Globally, Act Locally<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Most of us are familiar with the bumper-sticker,
&quot;Think Globally, Act Locally.&quot;  As it happens, this
slogan provides exactly the right framework for thinking about
the use of alternative fuel vehicles to achieve environmental
and national security objectives.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">As discussed above, two federal government
objectives can be addressed by expanding the use of AFVs:  1)
 Improving air quality in specific regions of the country; and,
2) reducing America's reliance on imported petroleum. The first
objective is defined by the CAA.  The second emerges primarily
from EPACT and CAFE.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The CAA correctly recognizes that the clean
air problem is local or regional in nature. Different atmospheric
conditions and other characteristics make prospects for one national
solution for smog reduction very unlikely.  For example, Atlanta
has a heavy background level of hydrocarbon emissions from trees,
while Chicago has heavier NOx emissions and little in the way
of natural hydrocarbon emissions.  Uniform national command-and-control
 regulations simply will not get the job done.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Energy security, on the other hand, is a national
problem.  Simply put, EPACT calls for a reduction in the aggregate
importation of petroleum products into the United States - an
objective that could in principle be met through the use of AFVs
anywhere in America.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The solution:  Think globally, act locally.
 Create national objectives, but implement them on a geographically
&quot;customized&quot; basis that focuses on achieving maximum
environmental benefits.   And, do so in a way that encourages
further innovation, so that the best technologies are brought
to market and applied where they can do the most good.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">To achieve these objectives, we propose the
creation of Environmental Innovation Areas (EIAs).</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The essence of the proposal is simple:  Allow
those regions for which the federal government has identified
specific environmental objectives to achieve those objectives
in a way that makes the most sense for each area.  Further, because
the objectives are (at least in part) national, provide national
resources to meet them. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In principle, the EIA concept could be applied
to address a wide variety of environmental problems which share
the national/regional characteristics of the clean air challenges
we have addressed in this paper.  However, we focus here on describing
a specific proposal for implementing EIAs to address the clean
air and national security benefits associated with AFVs.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Identifying Regional Candidates
for EIAs</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The boundaries of an EIA should be determined
by the environmental issue it is meant to address.  In the case
of smog, smog production is a local or regional phenomenon tied
directly to emissions from mobile and stationary sources of particular
pollutants.  An EIA set up to deal with smog should have geographic
boundaries covering the sources of the smog, regardless of whether
those boundaries are consistent with political boundaries, such
as a city or state.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The CAA addressed the regional nature of the
problem establishing 22 metropolitan nonattainment areas and the
12-state Ozone Transport Region (plus the state of California)
as controlling units.  Indeed, the CAA defined decision-making
organizations for each of these regions.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We propose that each of the 22 urban areas
plus the 12-state Ozone Transport Region and the state of California
be designated automatically as EIAs.  Further, any other region
wishing to establish an EIA should be allowed to apply for approval
by federal authorities for such designation.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">EIAs and Clean Air Standards</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EIAs should be granted open-ended flexibility
in achieving air quality goals based on EPA-approved interpretations
of national standards.<sup><a href="end.html">126</a>
</sup>  The measurement of their success should
be their progress toward achieving overall performance standards
based on air quality monitoring - not whether they use specific
technologies or follow specific command-and-control regulation.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Utilizing this flexibility, each EIA will employ
its own, unique package of control instruments to deal with its
unique problems.  In some cases, control of NOx is more important
than obtaining reductions in VOC.  In other cases, stationary
controls are more crucial than seeking additional emissions reductions
from mobile sources.  But each EIA will have one common element:
 their efforts will be outcome-based;  inputs alone will not count.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">To replace the current input-based approach
with one based on outcomes will require waiving numerous EPA and
other mandates.  To obtain such waivers, each EIA would specify
how it plans to achieve the nationally mandated smog-reduction
goals, including detailing the actions to be taken and the means
by which the region would monitor outcomes and enforce decisions.
 However, we would propose that EPA be required to approve all
initial waiver requests based on a standard of &quot;reasonable
evidence&quot; that the EIA's proposal would achieve the desired
goals.  Further, waivers should only be revoked if an EIA consistently
(e.g. three years running) fails to achieve the specified outcomes
in terms of emissions reduction.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">We expect that EIAs would examine a wide variety
of options for achieving their objectives, including: </FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Differential fuel taxes that reflect emission
characteristics for different vehicle fuels;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Provision of tax credits or deductions
for the purchase of AFVs and construction of refueling facilities;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Requirements that AFVs be used in particular
locations;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Purchase of clean fuel vehicles by public
entities, or incentives for purchase by private ones;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Inspection and maintenance programs that
provide low cost, effective means for assuring emission reductions;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Transportation plans that reduce the use
of private automobiles; and,</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Arial">Development of emissions trading schemes
that provide incentives for the use of cleaner fuels and technologies
and allow optimal tradeoffs between stationary and mobile source
emission reduction.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial"></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In addition to these tools, we are confident
that the implementation of EIAs will generate many new ideas,
as groups at the grass roots level who will live with (and pay
for) the EIAs' policies seek to find the most effective and efficient
solutions.  In general, we would expect less reliance on inflexible
command-and-control regulations, strict rules requiring centralized
inspection of vehicles and fleets, high taxes on emissions, and
burdensome transportation plans relative to the use of flexible
market-based approaches.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">With EIAs around the nation utilizing different
control instruments, a discovery process will occur that leads
to fresh approaches for improving environmental quality. EIAs
will learn from each other what works and what does not, what
are more efficient and less costly ways to meet the standards.
Metropolitan areas, states and regions are naturally involved
in a competitive market for growth and change, and environmental
quality is an important consideration for people and firms when
making location decisions. The means chosen for maintaining and
improving environmental quality matter as well.  If one region
can provide cleaner air at lower cost than another, then more
wealth will be produced in the low-cost region.  There will thus
be pressure on EIAs to develop and adopt the most innovative,
efficient and effective mechanisms to meet their goals.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">The Federal Role in EIAs</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The federal government will play a crucial
role as referee in the EIA process.  By statute, it defines the
clean air goals to be achieved.  The national standards should
reflect a public policy choice made by Congress and enforced by
the EPA.  For instance, the national ambient air quality standards
would be a baseline EIAs would first be challenged to achieve,
after which they are obviously free to go further.  Given rising
incomes and strong preferences for improved air quality, it is
likely that the EIA process would inspire a race to the top. 
Allowing flexibility places a heavier burden on air quality monitoring.
 The EPA would be challenged to provide better, more complete
data on emission levels, and to give regular progress reports
to EIAs.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The federal government also plays a key role
by leveling the playing field for competing fuels and AFVs.  For
example, federal tax policy currently favors electric vehicles
and penalizes the use of propane.  Vehicle taxes should be set
on the basis of gasoline equivalence, relying fundamentally on
the notion of taxes as a highway user fee.  Alternately, the federal
government should apply emissions-based taxes to all fuels that
affect truly national environmental concerns, such as upper atmospheric
conditions or emissions that travel across national boundaries
or large populous regions.  States and EIAs should be encouraged
to continue to use emission-based fuel taxes.  In addition, the
federal government should gear its subsidies for urban transportation
programs to encourage the use of clean fuel buses.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">EIAs and Energy Security</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EPACT, related executive orders and CAFE form
the second major force pushing the entry of AFVs into U.S. markets.
 Unlike improvements in air quality, which redound to the benefit
of people in local areas, a one-barrel reduction in imported oil
does not generate locally identifiable benefits but serves to
accomplish a national mandate.  Under EPACT, DOE is charged with
reducing American reliance on imported petroleum.  AFVs are an
important means of accomplishing this objective.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Currently, DOE is considering rules that could
require providers of alternative fuels, public sector fleets and
private fleet operators with 20 or more vehicles to increase their
purchase and use of AFVs, with the objective that AFVs will account
for 75 percent of new fleet purchases by the turn of the century.
 Presidential executive orders require similar mandates for federally
operated fleets.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">A requirement that the federal government itself
purchase AFVs is one thing. However, a requirement that private
firms and state and local governments purchase AFVs is an unfunded
mandate.  In the first instance the costs borne by the federal
government are visible; they are in the U.S. budget.  In the latter
instance, the costs are hidden but nonetheless real.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">In conjunction with EIAs, we propose that all
required purchases of AFVs be funded sufficiently to cover related
incremental costs.  For private firms, income tax credits or direct
payments would be preferred.  For public sector fleet purchases,
the federally provided offset may take the form of trades involving
other federal programs.  With all costs made visible, U.S. taxpayers
and their representatives can better appreciate the opportunity
cost of the mandate and more effectively allocate funds for that
purpose.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">What size budget would it take to fund an incremental
cost of mandated AFVs? One illustrative approach to answering
the question involves consideration of failed 1992 congressional
attempts to expand AFV purchases.<sup><a href="end.html">127</a>
</sup>  Under the proposed 1992 National
Energy Security Act, Congress described AFV purchase targets for
federal, state, local and private business fleets.  The bill called
for 1.2 million AFVs in private fleets by the year 2000 and twice
that number in operation by 2010.  Some 1.4 million light vehicles
were included in the 2010 count.  If, for example,  the current
incremental cost of $3,500 for CNG vehicles were budgeted, the
total cost of achieving the 2010 goal of an additional 1.4 million
light vehicles would be $4.9 billion. If spread over a 15-year
period, the annual cost would run $326 million.  (Although this
illustration is for light-duty vehicles, we would expect, at least
initially, much of the AFV budget to be concentrated in the purchase
of heavy-duty vehicles, which are less dependent on a distribution
infrastructure.  The incremental costs of these vehicles are highly
variable, depending on vehicle type.)</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">This cost could be at least partly offset by
using funds from a variety of existing federal programs designed
to promote the use of AFVs.  EPACT currently provides income tax
deductions of up to $2,000 for the purchase of light-duty AFVs
and greater amounts for heavy-duty vehicles.  Funds are also provided
through DOE's Clean Cities Program and through DOT programs to
promote AFVs.  These existing subsidies could be redeployed to
fund the incremental cost of AFV purchases through EIAs.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">An additional 1.4 million light vehicles, which
would be about 10 percent of the privately owned fleet, would
reduce annual oil consumption by about 14 million barrels and
emissions of VOCs by about 40,000 tons.  Although this constitutes
a relatively small percentage of total VOC emissions, through
the EIA process this reduction would be concentrated in the areas
where smog is of greatest concern.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">To achieve the maximum environmental benefit
from AFVs, funding priorities for AFV purchases should be determined
in conjunction with the EIAs.  Specifically, we propose a periodic
tournament process, managed by the Department of Energy, to establish
how much AFV funding each EIA should receive, with funding decisions
based on air quality conditions in the competing EIAs.  That is,
the first decision-making criterion in allotting AFV funding should
be to see which EIAs would achieve the greatest environmental
benefits by using AFVs.  Once ranked on the basis of how much
AFVs contribute to air quality gains in each EIA, the DOE would
then consider other factors, such as the availability of fuels
and the development of a critical mass for viable infrastructure
and markets, in making the final funding allotment.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Finally, federally mandated fuel economy standards
(CAFE) should be reexamined in the light of AFV technologies.
 An expansion of AFVs can have the same effect on oil importation
as higher CAFE standards, which carry a high cost in human life.
 We believe the increased use of AFVs can make CAFE unnecessary
and, ultimately, that CAFE can and should be eliminated.  Auto
producers will then be able to channel energies used currently
for achieving CAFE to designing and producing AFVs.</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Conclusion:  Environmental Innovation
Areas as a</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT FACE="Arial">Next Step in a New Environmental
Agenda<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The EIA concept can be used for managing most
forms of environmental pollution.  Few environmental challenges
are truly national in scope but typically local or regional in
nature.  Indeed, the history of environmental law indicates that
the federal government's first environmental regulation was aimed
at efforts to coordinate state and local actions.
<sup><a href="end.html">128</a></sup>  Even after
the formation of the federal blueprint in the 1970s, the federal
government continued to rely on states for operating federally-approved
programs and, in the case of water quality, setting water quality
goals for streams, rivers and lakes.  All attempts to impose uniform
standards across the entire country have met with frustration,
exemptions, delays and variable enforcement.  To some degree,
variations reflect differences in the nature of the pollution
problems encountered and the ability of communities to deal with
the national goals.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Embryonic EIAs may already be forming.  Under
DOE's Clean Cities program, almost 50 metropolitan areas have
submitted plans and gained approval for cooperative assistance
in promoting AFVs and clean air.<sup><a href="end.html">129</a></sup>
  Each designated city has its
own specialized plan for achieving clean air goals.  In some cases,
the plans include cooperative private/public efforts to expand
alternative fuel infrastructure along with efforts to be taken
by stationary sources to reduce emissions.  In others, the plans
involve transportation systems and expanded AFV fleets.  For example,
a school transportation agency in California's Long Beach Clean
City area is converting an aging fleet of 180 diesel-fueled school
buses to vehicles using CNG, methanol and advanced designed diesels.
 To assist in the process, Southern California Gas Company installed
a CNG refueling station, and the district is building an electric
recharging station for an electric powered demonstration school
bus.  In another case, leaders in Honolulu formed a coalition
to promote the use of propane, methanol and electricity as vehicle
fuels. The coalition plans to add 480 AFVs to the existing fleet
of 300. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">The Coachella Valley Region of California,
best known as the location of Palm Springs, provides a more complete
example of how the Clean Cities program could form a foundation
for EIA designation.<sup><a href="end.html">130</a></sup>
  Leaders across nine cities in the region
organized an association for promoting clean air.  By combining
the interests of industrialists, educators and operators of bus
companies, the association moved forward with a program that promotes
AFVs, improved transportation systems and the location of specialized
manufacturers in the area.  Their plan includes the production
of hydrogen fuels, making available CNG refueling units in newly
constructed homes, and the expansion of refueling facilities.
 The Coachella Valley now has the largest CNG refueling station
in Southern California along with mobile refueling units for commercial
users.  After converting 40 vehicles to CNG, the local bus company
has achieved some 30 tons of NOx emission reductions that it is
now seeking to sell in the Southern California emissions credit
market.  With a number of key stakeholders in place, the Coachella
Valley group could readily move to embrace larger environmental
goals and seek flexibility for attaining them as an EIA. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">An effort in North Carolina to achieve water
quality goals provides the best example of an operating EIA. 
North Carolina's Tar-Pamlico River Basin Association was formed
in 1988 for the purpose of achieving reductions in phosphorous
and nitrogen discharges in the Tar River and Pamlico Sound.
<sup><a href="end.html">131</a></sup> EPA
agreed to alter its command-and-control approach to mandatory
point-source controls, without which Tar-Pamlico could not achieve
the desired standard.  Instead, EPA allowed the Association to
meet a water quality performance standard.  Tar-Pamlico's solution
was a plan involving the trading of pollution reductions:  the
association facilitates trading between farmers who reduce their
discharge of nitrogen and phosphorous and municipal treatment
works that are required to reduce their discharge of the same
pollutants.  Funds for these trades come from members of the association
that pay discharge fees based on emission characteristics.  Even
more to the point, the Association members represent a regional
watershed, which is the relevant zone of control, that does not
conform to any particular political boundary.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">Visions of EIAs are also seen in other countries.
 For example, all French rivers are managed by autonomous and
distinct regional authorities.<sup><a href="end.html">132</a></sup>
  Each of the associations must
obtain its own funding, and each is accountable for improving
water quality.  In the United States, EPA's bubble and offset
policies for air pollution control, which allow low-cost sources
of pollution control to exchange emission reductions with higher
cost sources, represent steps in the direction of EIAs.<sup><a href="end.html>133</a></sup>  These
instruments decentralize control by allowing plant operators to
meet overall standards instead of meeting standards at each-and-every
source and to obtain pollution offsets from other plants.  In
other words, rudimentary forms of EIAs are emerging.
<sup><a href="end.html">134</a></sup></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial">EIAs represent a next logical step that can
be taken to move environmental protection forward. By focusing
on the appropriate zone of control; emphasizing outcomes, not
inputs; and, allowing flexibility in achieving desired goals,
environmental control authorities can assist the development of
incentive-based institutions that will more effectively yield
environmental improvement. </FONT>
<P>
<a href="sect5.html">Previous Section: Emerging AFV Niche Markets</a><p>
<a href="exec.html">First Section: Executive Summary</a><p>
<a href="end.html">End Notes</a>
</BODY>
</HTML>
