<HEAD>
<title>Plan to Abolish FCC Unveiled
 -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<H1>Plan to Abolish FCC Unveiled</H1>


<p>

The Progress & Freedom Foundation today unveiled a plan to abolish the
<A HREF="http://www.fcc.gov/">Federal Communications Commission</A> within three years and replace it with a
vastly smaller "Office of Communications Policy."<p>

The comprehensive plan was developed by a working group that includes
representatives from the American Enterprise Institute, The Brookings
Institution, Citizens for a Sound Economy, The Heritage Foundation, The
Hudson Institute, The Manhattan Institute and the University of California.
  The group was led by Progress & Freedom Foundation Chairman <A HREF="/pff/people/director.html">G.A. (Jay)
Keyworth, II</A>, former White House Science Advisor.<p>

"This plan represents the first step in a broader effort to replace the
outmoded regulatory structures of industrial-age government," Foundation
President <A HREF="/pff/people/director.html">Jeffrey Eisenach</A> said in releasing the report.  "The current system
cannot be reformed; it must be replaced, and the FCC is a great place to
start."<p>

"The government in Washington is still operating within a legal framework
designed when AM radio was cutting-edge technology.  If America wants to be
competitive in the global race to build the digital infrastructure of
Cyberspace, then wholesale changes in current policy must occur," added
Keyworth.<p>

The report, "<A HREF="telecom_revolution.html">The Telecom Revolution -- An American Opportunity,</A>" examines
existing statutes, rules and regulations, and offers detailed and specific
recommendations that they either be eliminated immediately, subjected to a
three year sunset provision, or retained but reassigned to the Office of
Communications Policy.<p>

"The FCC has caused endless delays in the adoption of new telecommunications
technology and services, costing the American economy and consumers hundreds
of billions of dollars in lost economic benefits," said Peter Huber of the
Manhattan Institute and a member of the working group.  "I hope Congress will
hold hearings this summer on the 'de-authorization' of the FCC," continued
Huber.<p>

Among the report's main features are:<p>

<UL>
<LI>Streamlining the 2,200-employee FCC into a vastly smaller Office of
Communications Policy.<p>

<LI>Privatizing the government monopoly on spectrum, thereby generating rapid
development of new technologies, new jobs and new services and billions in
revenue for federal deficit reduction.<p>

<LI>Subjecting the telecommunications industry to full competition by
eliminating and repealing government regulations that stifle new products,
new services and new job creation.<p>

<LI>Providing basic dialtone service for the truly needy but replacing the
complex, hidden cross-subsidies scheme with a more efficient and targeted
needs-based system.<p>
</UL>

"All too often, instead of promoting competition and innovation, the FCC is
captured by the forces of the status quo.  Given heightened competition and
the accelerating pace of technological advance, the costs of delay imposed by
the FCC are no longer acceptable," said Peter Pitsch of the Hudson Institute
and also a member of the plan's working group.<P>

Crafted under the auspices of The Progress & Freedom Foundation, a
Washington, D.C.-based think tank, the plan was put together in consultation
with a working group whose members included:<P>

<ul>
<A HREF="/pff/people/director.html">Dr. G.A. Keyworth II</A>, The Progress & Freedom Foundation<br>
<A HREF="/pff/people/director.html">Dr. Jeffrey A. Eisenach</A>, The Progress & Freedom Foundation<br>
David Colton, Esq., The Progress & Freedom Foundation<br>
Dr. Robert Crandall, The Brookings Institution<br>
James Gattuso, Citizens for a Sound Economy<br>
<A HREF="http://polar.ucdavis.edu/new/twh.html">Dr. Thomas W. Hazlett</A>, <A HREF="http://www.ucdavis.edu/">University of California, Davis</A><br>
Peter W. Huber, Esq., Manhattan Institute<br>
Dr. Thomas Lenard, The Progress & Freedom Foundation<br>
Peter Pitsch, Esq., Hudson Institute<br>
Kenneth Robinson, Esq., telecommunications consultant<br>
J. Gregory Sidak, Esq., American Enterprise Institute<br>
Adam Thierer, <a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>

</ul>

"It is time to consider the creation of a new regime that does not impede
competition in the process of purportedly protecting consumers from a
no-longer existing monopoly," said Robert Crandall of the Brookings
Institution and a working group member.<p>


<p>


</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>

