<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Cascadia Conference</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H2>PRESS RELEASE </H2>
<B><BR>
Press Contact: Rob Crowther (206) 287-3144<BR>
Conference registration: Julie Lanz (206) 287-3144<BR>
<BR>
</B>
<H1><CENTER>Cascadia tourism conference to christen Seattle's new Bell Harbor
international conference center</CENTER>
</H1>
<P><CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<P>SEATTLE-Tourism industry leaders from throughout Cascadia will converge
on Seattle's new convention center June 6-7 to focus efforts on highlighting
the regions attractions worldwide. The Cascadia &quot;mainstreet&quot; region
includes Oregon, Washington and British Columbia.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Tourism is one of the most important regional industries for Cascadia,&quot;
said Cascadia Project Director Bruce Agnew. &quot;By bringing everyone to
one place, to work together on how to promote the region and eliminate cross-border
barriers, this conference will be the key to focusing international attention
on Cascadia as a vacation destination and boosting annual tourism revenues.&quot;<BR>
As the world's tenth largest economy this vast Pacific Northwest region
- which also includes the states of Idaho, Montana, and Alaska as well as
the province of Alberta and the Yukon Territory - boasts tourism revenues
of nearly $20 billion (US$) and more than 100 million people annually visiting
the five states and two provinces and territory that make up Cascadia.<BR>
<BR>
This two day tourism conference, organized with the help of the Cascadia
Tourism Working Group led by the Port of Seattle, will bring together industry
leaders to strategize a regional outline of cooperative efforts, focusing
on off-peak season, to help benefit all of Cascadia. It will feature workshops
and seminars on resort destinations within Cascadia-such as Whistler B.C.
Ecotourism, adventure vacationing and regional sports issues like the Mariners,
Grizzlies, Commonwealth Games and the 2008 Olympic bid will also be among
the topics.<BR>
<BR>
Adam Leipzig, whose company Interscope Communications produced the hit films
Mr. Holland's Opus, Dead Poet's Society, and Good Morning Vietnam, will
talk about marketing the region to the television and movie industry to
increase the use of Cascadia for on-location filming.<BR>
<BR>
Ralph Munro Washington State Secretary of State, Rod Harris British Columbia
Asst. Dep. Minister of Tourism, Julie Courtis of the Oregon Tourism Commission
and Dick West President of Alaska Sightseeing Cruise West will be on hand
to moderate and facilitate discussion on Cascadia tourism and advertising
the region's appeal worldwide. The evening of June 6 will include Tourism
Vancouver's entertainment season program highlighting productions such as
Showboat, as well as the Grizzlies and Canucks.<BR>
<BR>
For more information call (206)287-3144.
<H3><CENTER><A HREF="twonation.html">More info on the Cascadia tourism conference<BR>
<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.cascadianet.com/">Additional Info from Cascadianet.com</A></CENTER>
</H3>
