<HEAD>

<TITLE>Advancing Medical Innovation: Remarks by Thomas Bliley -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>Advancing Medical Innovation: Health, Safety and the Role of Government in the 21st Century</h2>
Remarks by Chairman Thomas Bliley
<P>
 Good morning, ladies and gentlemen.  While I regret that I cannot
be with you in person today, it's nonetheless a pleasure to be
able to talk to you, as you begin your discussions, to shape a
new direction in the nation's thinking about the role of the federal
government in approving and regulating food products, drugs, and
medical devices.
<P>
 Last week, as you all know, we ended a 14-year gridlock, and
enacted sweeping new telecommunications reforms, the first overhaul
of this nation's communications laws since Marconi was alive.
<P>
 It is the most deregulatory bill in history, with an estimated
30 to 80 billion dollars in annual consumer and business benefits.
<P>
 Yesterday, after months of intensive work with the nation's governors
and the Blue Dog Democrats, we were able to secure unanimous,
bipartisan agreement by the governors to a historic restructuring
of the Medicaid and welfare programs.
<P>
 That will move responsibility away from Washington, and back
to the states, so they can deliver health care and welfare benefits
more fairly, more efficiently, and at lower cost.
<P>
 In the days ahead, our Committee will tackle another challenge,
in an effort to modernize the way we regulate foods and health
care products.
<P>
 Our goal here is the same kind of fundamental change that we
saw in telecommunications, and that we are working on in Medicaid
reform.  It is a simple objective.
<P>
 Opening up the marketplace, and stimulating innovation, while
continuing the protections that have afforded Americans a reliable
and safe supply of food, drugs, and medical devices.
<P>
 I certainly don't need to tell the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation
about the fundamental problems that exist in our nation's system
for regulating food and health care products.  I've heard them
in congressional hearings, and in countless meetings with my constituents.
<P>
 Your Foundation has described them in the report you issued today.
 We all want to stimulate innovation and development of lifesaving
new medicine and devices, and we all want them brought to the
patients who need them as quickly as possible.
<P>
 And we all want to continue consumer confidence in the safety
of those products.  We want the doctors and medical researchers
to communicate, to disseminate information, so patients can benefit
from the experience of others.
<P>
 But those goals are not achieved by the current regulatory structure.
 To accomplish those goals, we need fundamental structural change.
<P>
 My objective is a system of oversight of food and health care
products, in the 21st century, that is capable of matching the
developments that 21st century medical technology will doubtless
provide.
<P>
 The Progress and Freedom Foundation today will set forth a proposal
that seeks to establish a more efficient and innovative mechanism
to get safe products to the marketplace more quickly.
<P>
 One that utilizes private sector know-how to help meet the need
for government oversight.  The idea is not a new one, as you will
hear later today.
<P>
 Europe has had enormous success using private sector organizations
to conduct product reviews, reviews that, in the United States,
are exclusively being done by the FDA.
<P>
 Indeed, in other areas of government oversight, the United States
has already taken advantage of private-public cooperation.  In
fact, a substantial proportion of the foods that come under FDA's
jurisdiction are already overseen by nine federal organizations.
<P>
 I have yet to hear a good reason why safety reviews shouldn't
be performed by the private sector, or why safety practices cannot
be self-certified, or certified by third party inspection.
<P>
 In fact, President Clinton himself has proposed self-certification,
third party reviews of worker safety procedures.
<P>
 We have vast experience with third party reviews in the world's
greatest biomedical research institution, the National Institutes
of Health.  The NIH has achieved preeminence with a model using
non-governmental expertise to make research funding decisions.
<P>
 And its world-class research is conducted primarily by non-federal
research organizations.  There's no reason we should not turn
to those same scientists and institutions to help us better evaluate
new products.
<P>
 The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation today proposes a responsible
system of product review that keeps the federal government in
the critical role of deciding which products should go to market,
but which places greater reliance on private sector incentives
to drive the review process.  It ensures that government will
be involved only when necessary.
<P>
 For example, the simplest medical devices should not need to
undergo additional government approval, if they have already been
accepted by independent, private sector review organizations as
meeting clearly established, rigorous government standards.
<P>
 I want you to know that the Committee on Commerce will continue
to vigorously address the need for fundamental reform at the FDA.
<P>
 Chairman Barton has already held a series of Oversight and Investigative
Subcommittee hearings, in this regard and those hearings have
shown an agency in need of serious reform.
<P>
 Once Congress returns to Washington, later this month, I anticipate
further hearings in both the Oversight and Investigation Subcommittee,
and in Chairman Balarakis' Health Subcommittee, where we will
hear the views of distinguished Americans on what is wrong with
FDA, and what we should do about it.
<P>
 And I expect we will focus much of our attention on a system
for third party review.  I anticipate the first legislative hearing
will be held on February 27th.
<P>
 A number of FDA reform bills have already been introduced in
this Congress, and I expect to see several more, from members
of the Commerce Committee, that address the need for specific
reform in the areas of medical devices, drugs, biologics, and
food.
<P>
 An essential element of those proposals will be to assure that
the regulatory program for each category of products is suitable
for the particular product involved.
<P>
 Issues of safety and effectiveness are different, after all,
for each category of products.  And the regulation of each should
be no greater and no less than what is reasonably required.
<P>
 We should always strive to eliminate unnecessary regulatory burdens,
and that means a level of federal regulation no greater than is
appropriate, given the circumstances.
<P>
 Finally, and most importantly, let me assure each of you that
our regulatory proposals will allow greater, more reasonable reliance
on appropriate, non-governmental organizations to conduct product
reviews under appropriate FDA oversight.
<P>
 We will retain the FDA's critical role in monitoring the review
process, and ensuring compliance, but we will examine mechanisms
to transfer the reviews themselves to third party organizations
wherever appropriate.
<P>
 Again, I want to thank you for this opportunity to speak to you
this morning, even if not in person.  You have helped me, and
my Committee with your work today, and I am grateful.  Thank you,
and God bless you all.

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
</BODY>

