<HEAD>

<TITLE>Plan Kicks-Off FDA Reform  -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<i>February 7, 1996</i>
<p>

<h2>Plan Kicks-Off FDA Reform</h2> 
<P>
The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation today released a plan to
<a href="/pff/mip/fdatoc.html">replace FDA's current, obsolete approval mechanism</a> for new drugs
and medical devices with a decentralized process relying heavily
on private sector certification agencies.
<P>
The plan, released at a major conference sponsored by the Foundation,
calls for the creation of new, private certification organizations.
The FDA's role would shift from certifying and regulating products
to certifying and regulating these new entities.
<P>
The Foundation's report also criticized the current process for
being much too slow to bring new medical products to market, depriving
patients of treatments needed for them to live longer, healthier
lives.
<P>
&quot;As a physician I have seen people suffer when potential
help was just across the border. Pharmaceuticals and medical devices
available in Europe and Asia are not available in America because
we have a regulatory system that operates at its own slow place
and for its own convenience,&quot; said <a href="/pff/mip/sull0207.html">Dr. Louis Sullivan</a>, former
Secretary of Health and Human Services and Chairman of the Advisory
Committee that oversaw preparation of the proposal.
<P>
The report, <a href="/pff/mip/fdatoc.html"><I>Advancing Medical Innovation: Health, Safety and
the Role of Government in the 21st Century</I></a>, proposes replacing
the current FDA monopoly over approval with a competitive &quot;third
party&quot; review process. Under the plan, Drug or Device Certification
Bodies (DCBs) would compete for the most timely, efficient and
cost-effective methods to review new products. However, all existing
standards for safety and effectiveness would be maintained.
<P>
&quot;The reforms detailed in this plan will lead to greater efficiency
and cost-effectiveness via competition among the DCBs. Subject
to the legal standard of safety and effectiveness, DCBs will be
encouraged to devise innovative and more efficient ways of developing
drugs and getting them approved,&quot; said Dr. Henry Miller,
a co-author of the plan and the former founding director of FDA's
Office of Biotechnology.
<P>
Under the new plan, the FDA's primary function would be to certify
the quality of the third party reviewers, not to actually perform
the review function itself. While the FDA would retain authority
to issue the final approval before a product is marketed, the
plan creates a new appeal procedure in the event of disagreement
with a company and/or DCB. The FDA also retains a powerful post-marketing
system for monitoring the safety of products.
<P>
Many components of the plan draw from the experience with third
party reviewers in the European Union. &quot;In Europe, third
party reviewers compete with each other on the basis of price,
timeliness and availability. This results in our patients being
deprived of medical devices that are already approved in Europe.
We have taken the best of the European model in designing a new
approval system for America,&quot; said <a href="/pff/people/afellow.html#Epstein">Dr. Ralph Epstein</a>, a co-author of the report and professor of anesthesiology at the University
of Connecticut.
<P>
&quot;The FDA is currently a prototypical centralized, bureaucratic
regulatory agency that is cumbersome, slow and expensive. Not
only does the outmoded FDA approval process directly result in
jobs being exported overseas, but, most importantly, it denies
advances in medicine to patients who need them to live healthy
lives, or even to survive,&quot; said <a href="/pff/people/director.html#Eisenach">Jeffrey A. Eisenach</a>, President
of the Foundation.
<P>
Dr. Sullivan added that the plan &quot;is about freedom - about
choice, about alternatives, about helping people prevent illness
and injury, about successfully treating disease when it strikes.
Real reform must make the system more accessible, less costly
and less bureaucratic for all our citizens.&quot; 

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
