<html>
<head>
   <title>Symposium Remarks by Louis W. Sullivan, M.D. -- PFF
</title>
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#8C1717" vlink="#545454" alink="#FF0000" background="notebook.gif">
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<ul>
<blockquote>
<p><a href="http://www.pff.org/pff"><img src="pffdoc.gif" border=0 height=56 width=120 align=right></a></p>

<h2>The Symposium on Advancing Medical Innovation: &quot;Regulating Medical
Technology in the 21st Century&quot;</h2>

<p>Remarks by Louis W. Sullivan, M.D. </p>

<p><b>Introduction</b> </p>

<p>Thank you, <a href="http://www.pff.org/pff/people/sfellow.html#Lenard">Tom
(Lenard)</a>. I agree with much that has already been said in the morning
session. The current FDA regulatory review system is outdated, archaic,
costly, and wasteful. It is too bureaucratic, byzantine, and enigmatic.
It is time for thoughtful, workable, and innovative change in the FDA regulatory
review process. </p>

<p><b>Experience at HHS</b> </p>

<p>I have first hand knowledge of the cost and delay you discussed. I already
have spent four years trying to reform FDA from the top down. During my
tenure as Secretary of <a href="http://www.os.dhhs.gov">Health and Human
Services</a>, we undertook substantial reform to increase the flow of pharmaceuticals
and medical devices to the market - and I'm proud of the work we did. You
see, I agreed with the critics who argued that unnecessary cost, duplication,
and delay prolonged treatable illness and disability, and often cruelly
denied help for those who were dying. As Secretary, I spoke with people
who flew to Europe or Asia to obtain life-saving pharmaceuticals internationally.
As a physician, I was angry that many people suffered and died wen help
was just across the border. And I was shocked at how easily many people
turned to charlatans and con artists because they had lost faith in a regulatory
system that operated at its own pace, for its own convenience, pursing
its own agenda. As a former <a href="http://www.nih.gov/home.html">NIH</a>
grantee, I talked with researchers who were frustrated, and often defeated,
by the overwhelming and illogical regulatory maze that must be negotiated
before approval of new products. I understood that reform was a life and
death matter. And I knew that something has to be done - we could do better.
We had to do better. </p>

<p><b>Structural Reform Necessary</b> </p>

<p>Administratively there is much that can be done - and should be done.
But fundamental structural changes are also needed. This country must re-examine
the role and function of FDA regulatory review. We must work to make all
products on the market safe and effective. But we can no longer allow the
regulatory system to set up hurdles that are unnecessary, redundant, and
impractical - hurdles that increase costs and delay without warrant. </p>

<p><b>Endorsement of Report</b> </p>

<p>That is why I endorse the proposals in <a href="http://www.pff.org/pff/mip/fdatoc.html">today's
report</a>. They are a sound first step toward improving the way our country
reviews and approves pharmaceuticals and medical devices. Thanks to the
work of Drs. Epstein, Lenard, Miller, Tollison, Viscusi, and Wardell, we
now have two important components for reform - a vision of regulation that
can lead us into the 21st century and a set of workable proposals that
speed up the review process without sacrificing our government's guarantee
of safety or efficacy. I thank all of you for your hard work, your commitment,
and your vision - because today you are helping to change the way our citizens
will think about FDA regulatory review, and because you have started in
motion a process that will eventually help millions of our citizens who
desperately need access to pharmaceuticals and devices that have already
been proven safe and efficacious about but are not accessible on the market.
</p>

<p>Let me give you a comparative example. I was interested in a recent
article in the <i><a href="http://www.wsj.com">Wall Street Journal</a></i>,
reporting that Hoechst AG, the German chemical company, Merck, and Glaxo
Wellcome are all working on drugs that keep cells from malfunctioning by
blocking signal transduction. Such a development could revolutionize disease
prevention for allergic disorders, rheumatoid arthritis, osteoporosis,
and transplant rejection. There might also be a payoff in terms of controlling
cancer cells. I agree with John Kuriyan of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute
- research on signals inside cells &quot;is an area of explosive growth.&quot;
</p>

<p>But once this research on signal transduction is translated into new
pharmaceutical, how long will it take to get them into the hands of physicians
and patients under the current FDA regulatory system? And at what cost?
Under the current system we probably won't see any pharmaceuticals for
at least fifteen years. European and Japanese approval will probably happen
years before we get around to it. And the research cost to meet FDA regulations
- easily in the hundreds of millions of dollars. </p>

<p>Surely we can do better. Unfortunately, the current regulatory system
gives the Food and Drug Administration a monopolistic power to approve
new pharmaceuticals and medical devices for marketing. This system may
only benefit large pharmaceutical companies, who are best able to bear
the tens of millions of dollars necessary to gain FDA approval for one
pharmaceutical product. As a result, consumers pay more for medication.
The FDA also jealously controls the review process, often adding years
of duplicative study before giving approval. Again, as a result, consumers
have to wait longer for the life-saving and life-enhancing pharmaceuticals
they should have. And all of this cost and delay means that some pharmaceutical
companies abandon promising pharmaceutical products, conduct less expensive
testing overseas, and chill further innovation. Because the FDA review
process is not efficient, and actually drives up health care costs, we
must change that process as part of any coherent health system reform effort.
</p>

<p>But we must make the drug review process more efficient and speedy without
compromising safety and efficacy. For example, biotechnology companies
must be allowed to move more easily from pilot to full-scale production
facilities, and to modify their plants and manufacturing procedures without
prior FDA approval, if the risk is negligible. As you know, at the present
time, even minor changes require FDA approval. </p>

<p>Under today's proposals, a major step forward would be to allow third-party
review is common in Europe, but not here. I would like to see contract
review organizations, academic health centers, some professional organizations,
and other groups receive licenses to conduct review of pharmaceutical products,
thereby cutting industry costs and the time lag for drug review, while
making the review process more inclusive of other organization in the health
system. Such a change would also broaden our biomedical research base,
creating more opportunities for universities, institutions, and organizations
to become involved in the review process. There would be a tremendous educational
advantage for students and researchers involved in nongovernmental drug
certification bodies. More people would become invested in cutting edge
biomedical research, geometrically increasing the advantages from expanding
the frontiers of knowledge. </p>

<p>In addition, I agree that it is time for this country to adopt the European
approach and exempt from pre-market review up to 125 categories of low-risk
medical devices. I am pleased that a bill was recently introduces in the
Senate to designate that some classes of devices could be marketed without
FDA pre-notification and review. This proposal only covers a handful of
classes. In my view, we need to broaden the bill's scope to include all
classes of devices that pose no problems of safety or efficacy. </p>

<p>But, of course, the riskiest products should receive pre-marketing design
approval by a drug certification body. Pre-market FDA notification will
provide an additional check on the appropriateness of introducing a risky
medical device. </p>

<p>Finally, we must reduce the regulatory burden faced by the pharmaceutical
and medical device industries. Environmental assessments are not needed
for every individual drug. Individual batches of insulin do not need to
be certified. Redundant studies are not necessary, especially if extensive
testing has already been done in Europe. </p>

<p>I specifically endorse a streamlined appeals process through establishment
of a Medical Review Board at HHS. This will underline the accountability
of the Secretary of HHS to the American people, and provide a closer involvement
between FDA and the Office of the HHS Secretary. </p>

<p><b>The Bottom Line</b> </p>

<p>The real question is - whom are we trying to serve? If it is the patient,
then let's make the changes necessary to help the patient save money and
time, without compromising quality. If we are trying to serve the government,
we have in place a bureaucrat-friendly, convoluted, and wasteful system.
</p>

<p><b>Conclusion</b> </p>

<p>In the end, it will be a question of vision and leadership. Our vision
must be a patient priority. </p>

<p>Over the past several years I have spoken about the goals that must
guide health care reform, whether we are looking at changes in reimbursement
or alterations of pharmaceutical approval. In my view, real reform must
make the health care system more accessible for all of our citizens. It
must give them choices, empower them, and make the treatment more effective.
A patient priority - an emphasis on making the health care system more
user-friendly - must become an overriding philosophy. </p>

<p>In his autobiography, Nelson Mandela spoke of &quot;indivisibility of
freedom.&quot; We urged each of us to &quot;walk the long road to freedom&quot;
by recognizing that limitations on the freedom of some of us eventually
curtail the freedom of all of us. </p>

<p>Today's discussion is about freedom - about choice, about alternatives,
about helping people prevent disease, and successfully treat disease when
it strikes. Health people have more independence. Empowered people need
fewer government services. Free people can do better for themselves, and
make their life more rewarding and satisfying. </p>

<p>The proposals in this report will give our citizens more choices. It
will give them more control over their lives. We will have introduces reform
that assists the patient. And a patient priority is how we can best meet
the needs of our citizens. With such a vision, we can become powerful agents
for change. We can provide the leadership needed to secure a more compassionate,
more efficient, and more effective health care system. We can be a catalyst
for helping patients to become more empowered, to expand their range of
choices, to have more choices to evaluate, to have more pharmaceuticals
and medical devices to choose from, to have access to those pharmaceuticals
more quickly and without increased risk, and to become full partners in
providing top-quality health care for all Americans. You and I can do this,
if we always remember that the health care system should continue to be
structured to serve the patient. That is how we can help all of our citizens
to walk the long road to freedom. </p>

<p>Again, I applaud each of the authors of this remarkable and timely report.
And I appreciate the excellent work from Tom (Lenard), <a href="http://www.pff.org/pff/people/staff.html#Wright">Libby
(Wright)</a> and Rick (Teske). You have provided an important forum in
today's conference. </p>

<p>Thank you for inviting me to share these perspectives with you. </p>

<p>
<br></p>
</blockquote>
</ul>

<center><p>
<br><a href="http://www.pff.org/pff/footer.map"><img ismap src="footer.gif" border=0 height=21 width=272></a></p></center>

