<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Religion</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<PRE></PRE>
<H1><CENTER>Religion, Liberty &amp; Civic Life</CENTER>
</H1>
<PRE>

</PRE>
<H3>George Washington Fellows</H3>
<PRE>Discovery Institute's annual <A HREF="religion.html">George Washington Fellows Program</A> will be held this Summer from July 15 to
August 11, 1996. An intensive four-week seminar on religion and politics for upper-level undergraduates and
first-year graduate students, the program is designed to give Fellows an in-depth understanding of the role
religion can play in a free society.

In addition to regular classroom discussion sessions, there will be a number of special forums on specific issues
led by nationally-recognized scholars and thinkers. Past forums have been led by George Gilder, George
Weigel, Edwin Meese, and Program Fellows Stephen Meyer and Edward Larson.

Questions or requests for information should be directed to Dr. John West at Discovery Institute. Applications
may be obtained by calling 287-3144. The deadline for applications is April 26.


</PRE>
<H3>Upcoming conference</H3>
<PRE>The Religion, Liberty, and Civic Life Program will also sponsor a one-day conference on &quot;Faith and Politics&quot;
on August 10, 1996 at Seattle Pacific University. The proceedings from last Summer's conference, &quot;The Death
of Materialism,&quot; have recently been published as a special issue of The Intercollegiate Review. More
information on this year's conference may be found in the June issue of the Journal.


</PRE>
<H3>Book publication</H3>
<PRE>The University Press of Kansas will publish <I><A HREF="preface.html">The Politics of Revelation and Reason: Religion and Civic Life
in the New Nation</A></I>, the new work by Discovery Fellow John West. 

Described by noted historian Mark A. Noll as &quot;a fresh, well researched, and extremely well-balanced account
of religious-political connections in the early republic,&quot; the book by the Director of Discovery's Religion,
Liberty, and Civic Life Program will be released in May.  Though West's book focuses primarily on the past rather than the present, he thinks it holds many lessons for
today. 

&quot;The more I studied the early years of our nation,&quot; says West, &quot;the more I realized that present controversies
are simply a continuation of arguments that have been going on from the start. There is a tremendous amount
we can learn from how religion became involved in politics in early America. The issues may be different,
but the principles are the same.&quot;

Discovery members wishing to place prepublication orders for the book should call the Institute at 287-3144.
</PRE>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="marchjrn.html"><IMG SRC="dymored-back.gif" WIDTH="78"
HEIGHT="17" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"></A></CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>
