<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Symposium Remarks by George B. Rathmann -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<i>February 7, 1996</i>
<P>
<h2>The Symposium on Advancing
Medical Innovation:  &quot;Regulating Medical Technology in the
21st Century&quot;</h2>
<P>
Remarks by George B. Rathmann, Ph.D. 
<P> 
High costs to develop health care products in the United States
and the overly risk-averse attitudes of regulators impede the
ability of the research-based pharmaceutical industry to do what
it excels at: innovating in the discovery, testing, and marketing
of safe and effective products. The time required from drug discovery
to approval for marketing now requires approximately 12-15 years,
and time is a critical commodity: It represents therapies lost
to patients, revenues lost to companies, and research monies &quot;burned.&quot;
The financial burden has become staggering: The most recent estimate
(in 1990) was that the cost of each drug emerging from the end
of the pipeline was, on average, $359 million.
<P>
Attempts to &quot;streamline&quot; the drug approval process recently
have focused inappropriately on the end game of drug development;
that is, on the final marketing approval for a new drug. The time
needed to reach the stage of filing for marketing approval represents
90 percent of the costs of drug development. This time is often
dramatically extended by overly conservative dosing regimens (limiting
dosage to a single dose for up to one year), extended observation
periods between patients and requiring FDA meetings and discussions
between subphases of the clinical study. Companies' researchers
and regulatory affairs professionals spend progressively more
time and resources meeting unnecessary requirements and shifting
requests.
<P>
There seems to be no means for correcting the FDA reviewers and
managers who - no doubt with the best of intentions - are inappropriately
slow or conservative and who, thereby, cause a drug to be delayed
or even abandoned.
<P>
<a href="/pff/mip/fdatoc.html">The Progress and Freedom Foundation's proposal</a> addresses some
of these shortcomings forthrightly and cleverly, by altering the
basic incentives and disincentives that drive the current system.
By transferring much of the FDA's oversight of the IND process
and marketing approval to non-governmental expert bodies which
have a strong incentive both to maintain high product standards
and expedite the drugs through the development pipeline, the system
is made altogether more rational and productive.
<P>
The improvement is manifest in three ways. First, the reforms
apply to virtually the entire drug process. Second, non-governmental
bodies, competing with one another for clients, are encouraged
to be expert, fast, and innovative. Third, there are potent fail-safe
mechanisms to assure the quality of the oversight.
<P>
I would emphasize that the reforms proposed by the Progress and
Freedom Foundation are important and conservative. The standards
for safety and efficacy are retained; and the FDA retains a substantial
role in certifying the non-governmental bodies, issuing final
sign-offs for marketing approval, overseeing regulatory compliance
and broadly overseeing and accumulating safety data. This is a
regime that will benefit both patients and industry. It should
establish a benchmark for the regulatory reform proposals that
will be discussed at Congressional hearings during the coming
weeks.
<P><br>
<I>George Rathmann is CEO and Chairman of the Board of ICOS Corporation
and Chairman of the Board, emeritus, of Amgen, Inc. </I>

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
