<HEAD>
    <TITLE>High Tech</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><CENTER>High Technology &amp; Public Policy</CENTER>
</H1>
<PRE>
Discovery Senior Fellow George Gilder continues to be widely-published and sought after for his thoughts
on the future of high technology and telecommunications. Gilder's &quot;Telecosm&quot; series is featured in each issue of the highly influential Forbes ASAP magazine. His work
was the subject of a lengthy cover story in the March 1996 issue of Wired magazine. In addition, his theories
were the focal point for a piece in the January 1996 issue of the same magazine.

Frequently testifying before the U.S. Congress, <A HREF="ggtstmny2.html">(read Gilder's April testimony)</A> Gilder will next appear in April before the Senate Commerce
Committee on the need for change in spectrum allocation policy and the future of the FCC. In late March,
Gilder will premiere an eight hour multimedia presentation on the technological future, developed at Discovery
recently. The first showings: a conference of 1,000 business executives in Brazil, followed by presentations
in Japan and Italy. In addition to his work on high technology, Gilder has written a number of notable articles recently on other
subjects: on the immigration debate (&quot;Geniuses from Abroad&quot;) in the Wall Street Journal, and on welfare
reform (&quot;How Welfare Seduced Sam Brewer&quot;) in the February 1996 Reader's Digest. </PRE>
<H3>Program Notes</H3>
<PRE>Frank Gregorsky, former chief assistant to Rep. Newt Gingrich and a Discovery Fellow, will move to Seattle
this Spring. He is currently completing his latest work editing the recent speeches and presentations of George
Gilder.


</PRE>
