<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE> REAL REFORM OR PILOT PROGRAMS? -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2></h2>
<P>
<h2>
 REAL REFORM OR PILOT PROGRAMS?
</h2>

by Thomas M. Lenard <p>


<br>
The most important idea now under consideration for reforming the Food and

Drug Administration is to permit manufacturers to use private organizations,

accredited by the FDA, to certify the safety and effectiveness of their new

drugs and medical devices.  This idea is central to the FDA reform

legislation on which the House will hold hearings this week, and is also an

element in the Senate Bill.<p>

Faced with a mountain of evidence supporting third-party review, from both

Europe and from U.S. pilot projects, the FDAs only response is to propose

yet another pilot project  for third-party review of low-risk medical

devices.  Let us hope the Congress will see this for what it is --

bureaucratic stonewalling by an agency trying to protect its turf -- and

conclude that the time for pilot programs is past.
<p>
Third-party review is of critical importance to FDA reform because it

addresses the fundamental cause of current deficiencies in drug and device

oversight -- the FDAs "monopoly" on new product approvals.  Like any other

monopoly, the FDAs stranglehold on entry to clinical research and new

product approvals means there is no effective institutional check on the

regulatory creep that inexorably has added time, costs, and unpredictability

to the review and approval process.  Over the last thirty years, the time

required to bring a new drug to market, from the test tube to the patient,

has increased steadily, from a little more than six years in the mid-1960s to

almost 15 years currently.
<p>
The viability of third-party review as a solution to the FDAs problems is

well established.  European medical device regulation is based entirely on a

system of competing, private, government-certified "notified bodies."
<p>
 Manufacturers retain these companies to certify compliance with a large set

of design and production standards.  With the exception of low-risk devices,

which manufacturers can self-certify, a medical device can gain access to the

European market only through one of these notified bodies.  Because of this

system, a product that requires six years to bring to market in the United

States takes four years in Europe.  As a result, medical device manufacturers

in large numbers are first introducing their products offshore, and American

patients increasingly are receiving therapies that are several generations

behind those available in Europe.
<p>
In the case of pharmaceuticals, private entities in this country have

performed all functions including implementing clinical development programs,

preparing New Drug Applications (NDAs) and even, on a pilot-project basis,

conducting final reviews.  In 1992, as part of a project to study the use of

outside experts, the Mitre Corporation was chosen to review five

"supplemental" NDAs (applications for new uses for already-approved products)

using FDAs statutory criteria.  They were consistent with FDAs policies and

the agency found no reason to overturn them.  The Mitre reviews were by all

accounts high quality and low cost.  And, they were conducted very

efficiently:  While the FDA takes an average of 28.3 months for its

supplemental reviews (according to data collected by Joseph DiMasi at Tufts),

Mitre completed its reviews in from two to four months.
<p>
The FDAs new proposed pilot project is so tepid that Rep. Jim Greenwood, who

is leading FDA reform efforts in the House, was prompted to observe:  "With

American heart patients having to travel to Italy for life-saving cardiac

stents, with FDA delays causing one-fifth of our medical device industry

moving overseas, the best the FDA can come up with is a pilot program for

third party review of tongue depressors!"
<p>
When the European system of device regulation has been so successful that it

is in the process of capturing our medical device industry, another pilot

program is no more than a delaying tactic.  For proof, we may simply ask what

use the FDA has made of lessons learned from its last pilot.  The answer:

 Despite the success of the Mitre project, the FDA has not increased the use

of outside reviewers.  So much for FDA pilot programs!
<p>
Meaningful FDA reform must address the agencys certification monopoly and

introduce competitive pressures into the drug and device approval processes.
<p>
 As long as the only route to the American market is through the FDA, the

development of new medical products will continue to be plagued by

unnecessary costs and delays and the adverse trends in product availability

and development times are likely to continue.
<p>
While third-party review would produce radical reform, it is not a radical

idea; the Europeans have been using third parties for years to certify their

medical devices.  Could we ask for a better "pilot program"?






<P>
<blockquote>

