<H1><CENTER>Discovery News &amp; Notes</CENTER>
</H1>
<PRE>

</PRE>
<H3>New Discovery Institute fellows</H3>
<PRE>Edwin Meese III and Lisa Brownlee have been appointed Adjunct Fellows of Discovery Institute.

Meese, counsellor to the President from 1981 to 1985 before becoming U.S. Attorney General from 1985 to
1988, currently holds the Ronald Reagan Chair in Public Policy at The Heritage Foundation in Washington,
D.C. He is the author of With Reagan: The Inside Story, published in 1992.

Brownlee is an attorney practicing with the Dutch law firm of Trenite Van Doorne in Amsterdam. A recent
Fellow at the Max Planck Institute in Munich, her practice includes U.S. and international copyrights and
licensing, U.S. and Benelux trademark matters, and European Community intellectual property and
competition law matters. She recently published several articles on intellectual property law. 

</PRE>
<H3>Two new Discovery board members</H3>
<PRE>William D. Ruckelshaus, Chairman of Browning-Ferris Industries, Inc. and former head of the Environmental
Protection Agency, and Mark Ryland, Senior Program Manager at Microsoft Corporation, have been elected
to the Board of Directors of the Discovery Institute.

Ruckelshaus became the EPA's first Administrator when the agency was formed in 1970 and served until 1973. 
He was reappointed by President Reagan to become the fifth EPA head in 1983, serving in that capacity until
1985. Among other positions in his distinguished career, he has been Acting Director of the Federal Bureau
of Investigation, Deputy Attorney General of the U.S., and Senior Vice President of the Weyerhaeuser
Company. 

Ryland heads Microsoft's OLE/Cairo Windows NT group, which is responsible for Microsoft's distributed
object system infrastructure for the next generation intranet and internet applications development. In addition,
Ryland heads OLE's marketing, technical support, and business development divisions. He began his career
in the legal field in Washington, D.C., concentrating on communications law, computers, and government
contracts. He joined Microsoft in 1991 as a Senior Architectural Engineer.

</PRE>
<H3>Events update</H3>
<PRE>Sixty-five members and guests heard Canadian author Gordon Gibson speak on his country's constitutional
and political crisis last December 5 at a Discovery luncheon program. Gibson is now syndicated in Canada's
national newspaper, the Globe and Mail, each Tuesday....Dr. Richard Judy, Director of the Hudson Institute's
Center for Central European and Eurasian Studies, spoke on the upcoming Russian presidential elections to
an audience of 80 on February 16 at a Discovery luncheon. Judy was introduced by Dr. Herbert J. Ellison,
Discovery Advisory Board Member and University of Washington expert on Russia and the former Soviet
Union.....Discovery's Cas- cadia Project hosted a two-day Metropolitan Forum, featuring business and
government leaders from Seattle, Portland, Oregon and Vancouver, British Columbia on February 22 and 23. 
Nationally-syndicated columnist Neal Peirce was the featured keynote speaker....Discovery Fellow (and Netscape Communications General Counsel) Roberta Katz spoke to an audience of
700 at the Downtown Seattle Rotary Club on March 6 on &quot;Rough Justice: Our Outmoded Adversarial System
of Justice and How to Reform It,&quot; an introduction to her soon-to-be-published book .....Discovery Institute was
a co-sponsor of a Washington Council on International Trade program featuring Douglas Hogg, Chief
Executive of Britain's Private Finance Panel, on March 8.....Robert Merry, Executive Editor of Congressional
Quarterly, spoke to 50 members and guests at a March 13 Discovery luncheon program on the upcoming U.S.
congressional elections. Merry's recent book, Taking on the World: Joseph and Stewart Alsop - Guardians
of the American Century, was the front page review in the February 25 New York Times Book Review.</PRE>
