<HEAD>
    <TITLE>William Dembski</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<P><CENTER><A HREF="crsc.html"><IMG SRC="crscweblogo.gif" WIDTH="248" HEIGHT=
"76" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></CENTER>
<H3><CENTER>William Dembski<BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="dembski.gif" WIDTH="150" HEIGHT="144" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"><BR>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="bigbluebar.gif" WIDTH="364" HEIGHT="5" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></CENTER>
</H3>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>William A. Dembski is a cross-disciplinary scholar who holds degress
in mathematics (Ph.D., University of Chicago), philosophy (Ph.D., University
of Illinois at Chicago), and theology (M. Div., Princeton Theological Seminary).
Dr. Dembski has done post-doctoral work at MIT, University of Chicago, Northwestern
University, Princeton University, and Cambridge University. He has been
a National Science Foundation doctoral and post-doctoral fellow. His publications
range from mathematics to philosophy to theology. He is currently a visiting
scholar at the University of Notre Dame's Center for Philosophy of Religion,
as well as the associate editor of the journal <A HREF="crsclinks.html"><I>Origins
and Design</I>.</A> He has recently completed a monograph entitled <I>The
Design Inference</I>, which describes the logic whereby people infer intelligent
causes.</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
