<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H1><CENTER>Cascadia</CENTER>
</H1>
<PRE>

Discovery 's Cascadia Project is host to a <A HREF="twonation.html">regional tourism conference</A> to be held June 6-7, 1996 at the Port of
Seattle's new Bell Harbor Conference Center.

The Cascadia Tourism Conference is designed to educate tourism leaders on regional cross-border initiatives
for commerce, conservation, and marketing. The conference will also explore new opportunities that
complement established partnerships. In addition, conference organizers hope to achieve greater support for
efforts to relieve port of entry congestion, enhance immigration clearances, and improve transportation
infrastructure and connections in the region. 

A Regional Tourism Fair, featuring displays from visitor associations, attractions, and tour operators, will be
held concurrently with the conference. Tourism industry practitioners are encouraged to contact Bruce Agnew or Stephanie Bowman at 287-3404
for information on workshops and general sessions as well as costs and registration for the two-day
conference.

The Cascadia Project's conference,&quot;The Cascadia Rail Stakeholders Session: Keeping Oregon Competitive,&quot;
has been rescheduled to April 12, 1996. To be held in Salem, the conference will feature an address by
Oregon Governor John Kitzhaber....The Cascadia Project is undertaking a year-long feasibility study on
Seattle's bid for the 2008 Summer Olympics for the Washington State Department of Community, Trade, and
Economic Development.....Over the past few months, the Cascadia Project has been assisted in its work by
Discovery Interns Marshall Sana and Jill Curtis.
</PRE>
