Now, a modern economist, because all modern government economists start,
and all -- virtually all bureaucrats and academics start with the idea of
continuities, so if you're going to measure demand, the demand is for
postal service.  Then you say:  somebody invented the fax.  But there was
no demand for the fax.  Because nobody knew it existed.  The second they
learned it existed, guess what?  There is huge demand for the fax.  Huh?
Now it's e-mail. Cellular telephones.  There were no cellular telephones.
People had very expensive radio telephones which only very, very wealthy
people or government institutions could afford, and then one morning
somebody invented the cellular phone.
<P>
How many of you have a cellular phone?  Look at this.  I mean, what a --
now, granted, you're an upper middle-class group of people and you're all
