<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<H3><I>From the Fall 1995 Discovery Journal:</I></H3>
<H1><CENTER><TT>What the experts are saying about George Gilder </TT></CENTER>
</H1>
<H3>Senior Fellow <A HREF="gildrbio.html">George Gilder</A> is always a
subject of conversation due to his role as a contributing editor to Forbes
ASAP. In recent letter's to Forbes ASAP here's what some of the telecommunications
industry leaders are saying about Gilder's revolutionary ideas about the
future of telecommunications, telecomputing and the Internet. </H3>
<HR>
<DL>
<DD>&quot;I'd like to compliment George Gilder for so eloquently articulating
Sun's nearly decade- old credo: `The network is the computer.' I believe
in Gilder's thesis that we are, indeed, at the onset of the age of network-accessed,
disposable software.&quot;<B>-Scott McNealy, CEO, Sun Microsystems </B>
<DD><BR>
<DD>&quot;To report technology history accurately is a difficult task requiring
percipience, perspiration, and perspective. Gilder has done it.&quot;-<B>Larry
Tesler, Vice-President, Apple Computer </B>
<DD><BR>
<DD>&quot;Gilder is dead-on right that hardware and operating systems will
become subordinate to the network: that the network will, in effect, beAcome
enverything an the only thing. And he's right, too, about the evolution
and impact of the Internet and the resultant focus on content.&quot;-<B>Bert
C. Roberts, Jr., Chairman and CEO, MCI Communications</B> 
<DD><BR>
<DD>&quot;Once again, George Gilder's got it right. His guide to the past
and future of the Net is on the digital dime.&quot; <B>-Nicholas Negroponte,
Director, MIT Media Lab</B> <BR>
<HR>
</DL>
